im|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|13\n|{{FRA}}\n|2017, 2018, 2019\n|[[Paris]]\n|State visit,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-has-traveled-to-france-participant-at-the-conference-of-paris|title=President Tha\u00e7i has traveled to France, participant at the Conference of Paris|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2017-12-08}}</ref> Working visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://telegrafi.com/thaci-takon-presidentin-francez-kosova-eshte-mirenjohese-frances-per-ndihmen-ndaj-kosoves/ |last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|14\n|{{SUI}}\n|2018\n|[[Davos]]\n|Working visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.president-ksgov.net/sq/lajme/presidenti-thaci-panelist-ne-forumin-ekonomik-boteror-ne-davos-te-zvicres|title=Presidenti Tha\u00e7i panelist n\u00eb Forumin Ekonomik Bot\u00ebror n\u00eb Davos t\u00eb Zvicr\u00ebs|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|15\n|{{KOR}}\n|2018\n|[[Pyeongchang]]\n|[[Pyeongchang 2018]] Opening Ceremony<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-attends-the-opening-of-the-winter-olympics-in-pyeongchang|title=President Tha\u00e7i attends the opening of the Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|16\n|{{MKD}}\n|2018, 2019\n|[[Skopje]]\n|State visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-visits-macedonia-meets-with-institutional-and-political-leaders|title=President Tha\u00e7i visits Macedonia, meets with institutional and political leaders|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n|-\n|17\n|{{ARM}}\n|2018\n|[[Yerevan]]\n|Francophonie Summit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-attended-the-opening-of-the-17th-francophonie-summit|title=President Tha\u00e7i attended the opening of the 17th Francophonie Summit|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n|-\n|18\n|{{BLR}}\n|2018, 2019\n|[[Minsk]]\n|Working visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-in-belarus-agreement-for-mutual-recognition-and-peace-in-balkans|title=President Tha\u00e7i in Belarus: Agreement for mutual recognition and peace in Balkans|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2018-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-attends-the-opening-of-the-minsk-2019-european-olympic-games|title=President Tha\u00e7i attends the opening of the Minsk 2019 European Olympic Games|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|19\n|{{GER}}\n|2019, 2020\n|[[Munich]], [[Berlin]]\n|Working visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/sq/lajme/presidenti-thaci-panelist-ne-konferencen-e-sigurise-ne-munih|title=Presidenti Tha\u00e7i panelist n\u00eb Konferenc\u00ebn e Siguris\u00eb n\u00eb Munih|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-travelled-to-berlin|title=President Tha\u00e7i travelled to Berlin|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n|-\n|20\n|{{SVK}}\n|2019\n|[[Bratislava]]\n|[[Globsec]] Forum<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-travels-to-slovakia-tomorrow-participates-in-the-bratislava-forum|title=President Tha\u00e7i travels to Slovakia tomorrow, participates in the Bratislava Forum|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|21\n|{{JPN}}\n|2019\n|[[Tokyo]], [[Osaka]]\n|State visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-travels-to-japan-on-a-state-visit-on-sunday-where-he-will-expected-by-the-emperor-and-prime-minister-abe|title=President Tha\u00e7i travels to Japan on a state visit on Sunday, where he will expected by the Emperor and Prime Minister Abe|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-attends-the-solemn-dinner-hosted-by-the-prime-minister-of-japan|title=President Tha\u00e7i attends the solemn dinner hosted by the Prime Minister of Japan|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n|-\n|22\n|{{MON}}\n|2019\n|[[Monte Carlo]]\n|Working visit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.president-ksgov.net/en/news/president-thaci-in-monaco-kosovo-excelled-in-sports-thanks-to-the-support-of-its-allies|title=President Tha\u00e7i in Monaco: Kosovo excelled in sports thanks to the support of its allies|last=Tha\u00e7i|first=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim|work=President of the Republic of Kosovo - Hashim Tha\u00e7i|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n*{{Flag|Albania}}: On 20 June 2008 received a copy of the key of the city of [[Tirana]] on the occasion of his state visit to Albania.<ref>[http://www.tirana.gov.al/Celesi_qytetit/raifaizen-rama-041.jpg Tha\u00e7i receives copy of the key of the City of Tirana], tirana.gov.al; accessed 14 July 2015 (in Albanian)</ref>\nAlso on 20 June, Tha\u00e7i was awarded the Honorary Citizen of the city of [[Vlor\u00eb]], for his \"historic role in making Kosovo an independent state\".<ref>[http://www.bashkiavlore.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=405&Itemid=151 Tha\u00e7i becomes honorary citizen of Vlora], bashkiavlore.org; accessed 5 October 2016 (in Albanian)</ref>\nIn January 2015 Hashim Tha\u00e7i was awarded the Doctor Honoris Causa from the University of Tirana, for his contribution in peace-building in Western Balkans, promoting the process of European integrations and achieving the historic Brussels Agreement with Serbia.\nOn 4 October 2016 the President of Kosovo was awarded Honorary Citizenship of [[Shkod\u00ebr]], in a ceremony led by the Mayor of this northern Albanian city.\n\n*{{Flag|Switzerland}}: On 1 July 2012, Tha\u00e7i received a Doctor Honoris Causa degree as a Doctor of International Relations from the [[Geneva School of Diplomacy]] in a ceremony held in that city. Previous recipients of this award include [[Martin Gray (Holocaust survivor)|Martin Gray]], a [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivor and writer; [[Adolf Ogi]], the former president of Switzerland; and [[Jos\u00e9 Ramos-Horta]], President of [[East Timor]] and a [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winner.<ref>[http://www.kryeministri-ks.net/?page=2,9,2966 Profile], kryeministri-ks.net; accessed 14 July 2015.</ref>\n*{{Flag|United States of America}}: In 2014, Albanian and Serbian Caucuses of US Congress nominated President Tha\u00e7i and Serbian FM [[Ivica Da\u010di\u0107]] for Nobel Peace Prize, for their role in achieving the Serbia-Kosovo peace deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zeriamerikes.com/a/thaci-dacic-ashton-nobel/1815968.html |title=Tha\u00e7i, Da\u00e7i\u00e7, Ashton em\u00ebrohen p\u00ebr \u00e7mimin Nobel}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Montenegro}}: On 4 April 2015, on [[Ulcinj Municipality Day|Ulcinj Day]], Tha\u00e7i received the title of ''Honorary Citizen of Ulcinj'' by the town's municipal government.<ref>[http://mne.ul-info.com/svecana-sjednica-so-ulcinj-rama-i-taci-pocasni-gradjani/#prettyPhoto Tha\u00e7i receives title of ''Honorary Citizen of Ulcinj''], mne.ul-info.com, 4 April 2015; accessed 14 July 2015. (in Albanian)</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{notes|notes=\n{{efn|name=name|{{lang-sq|Hashim Tha\u00e7i}}. {{lang-sh|Ha\u0161im Ta\u010di, \u0425\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043c \u0422\u0430\u0447\u0438}}.}}\n{{efn|name=status|{{Kosovo-note}}}}\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|author=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|title=Britannica Book of the Year 2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IaecAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA107|date=1 March 2009|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|isbn=978-1-59339-232-1|pages=107\u2013}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book|last1=Boyes|first1=Roger|last2=Jagger|first2=Suzy|title=New State, Modern Statesman: Hashim Tha\u00e7i \u2013 A Biography|year=2018 |publisher=Biteback Publishing|isbn=9781785903304|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rsBHDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=New+State,+Modern+Statesman:+Hashim+Tha%C3%A7i+%E2%80%93+A+Biography#v=onepage&q=New%20State%2C%20Modern%20Statesman%3A%20Hashim%20Tha%C3%A7i%20%E2%80%93%20A%20Biography&f=false|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hashim Thaci}}\n* [http://www.kryeministri-ks.net/?page=2,1 Prime Minister of Kosovo Official Website]\n* [http://www.pdk-ks.org/ PDK] Partia Demokratike e Kosov\u00ebs ''(in Albanian)''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071123103615/http://www.pdk-ks.org/site/?id=5,49,0,50,a,1467ttp Kryetari Tha\u00e7i: Populli i Kosov\u00ebs dhe U\u00c7K-ja ishin nj\u00eb] A Tha\u00e7i interview by \"Kosova Sot\" daily ''(in Albanian)''\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7133515.stm BBC News Profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060309004623/http://www.usip.org/events/2006/0112_kosovo.html Tha\u00e7i comments on the future of Kosovo at United States Institute of Peace]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bujar Bukoshi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Kosovo]]|years=1999\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nexhat Daci]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Agim \u00c7eku]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Kosovo]]|years=2008\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Isa Mustafa]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Enver Hoxhaj]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Kosovo)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Petrit Selimi]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Atifete Jahjaga]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Kosovo]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bajram Rexhepi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Democratic Party of Kosovo|Democratic Party]]|years=2004\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kadri Veseli]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{KosovoPres}}\n{{KosovanPMs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thaci, Hashim}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party of Kosovo politicians]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Kosovo Albanians]]\n[[Category:Kosovan soldiers]]\n[[Category:Kosovo Liberation Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Skenderaj]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Prime ministers of Kosovo]]\n[[Category:University of Pristina alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Zurich alumni]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "name_user": "CelebrityBuzz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar Correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hashim_Tha%C3%A7i"}
{"title_page": "26th Academy Awards", "text_new": "{{short description|Award ceremony presented by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences for achievement in filmmaking in 1953}}\n{{Infobox film awards\n| number           = 26\n| award            = Academy Awards\n| image            = 26th Annual Academy Awards at RKO Pantages Theater in Los Angeles, 1954.jpg\n| caption          = \n| date             = March 25, 1954\n| site             = [[Pantages Theatre (Hollywood)|RKO Pantages Theatre]]<br>[[Hollywood, California]] <br>[[New Century Theatre|NBC Century Theatre]]<br>[[New York City]], New York\n| host             = [[Donald O'Connor]] (Los Angeles)<br>[[Fredric March]] (New York City)\n| best_picture     = ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''\n| most_wins        = ''From Here to Eternity'' (8)\n| most_nominations = ''From Here to Eternity'' (13)\n| network          = [[NBC]]\n| duration         = \n| last             = 25th\n| next             = 27th\n}}\n\nThe '''26th Academy Awards ceremony''' was held on March 25, 1954. It took place at the [[Pantages Theatre (Hollywood)|RKO Pantages Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], and the [[New Century Theatre|NBC Century Theatre]] in New York City.\n\nThe second national telecast of the Awards show drew an estimated 43 million viewers. [[Shirley Booth]], appearing in a play in Philadelphia, presented the Best Actor award through a live broadcast cut-in, and privately received the winner's name over the telephone from co-host [[Donald O'Connor]]. (Actor [[Fredric March]] co-hosted from New York City.) [[Gary Cooper]] filmed his presentation of the Best Actress award in advance on a set in Mexico, with O'Connor announcing the winner's name.\n\nAll the major winners in this year were black-and-white films. The big winner was [[Fred Zinnemann]]'s ''[[From Here to Eternity]]'', with 13 nominations and eight awards including Best Picture, Best Supporting Actor, Best Supporting Actress, Best Director, Best Screenplay ([[Daniel Taradash]]), Best Cinematography (Burnett Guffey), Best Sound, and Best Film Editing. All five of its major actors and actresses were nominated, with secondary players [[Donna Reed]] and [[Frank Sinatra]] taking home Oscars. The film was based on [[James Jones (author)|James Jones]]' controversial, best-selling novel about Army life on a Hawaiian (Oahu) military base just before the [[Pearl Harbor]] attack and World War II, illustrating the conflict between an individualistic private ([[Montgomery Clift]]) and rigid institutional authority (exemplified by the Army). Its achievement of eight awards matched the then record held by ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' (1939). The record was tied again the following year by ''[[On the Waterfront]]'' (1954). [[Walt Disney]] won four awards, which set the record for the most Oscars won in the same year.\n\n[[William Holden]]'s speech for Best Actor for his role in ''[[Stalag 17]]'' was simply \"Thank You\", making it one of the shortest speeches ever; the TV broadcast had a strict cutoff time which forced Holden's quick remarks. The frustrated Holden personally paid for advertisements in the Hollywood trade publications to thank everyone he wanted to on Oscar night. He also remarked that he felt that either [[Burt Lancaster]] or [[Montgomery Clift]] should have won the Best Actor Oscar for ''[[From Here to Eternity]]'' instead of him.\n\n==Awards==\nWinners are listed first and highlighted in '''boldface.'''<ref name=\"Oscars1954\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1954 |title=The 26th Academy Awards (1954) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=May 31, 2015 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093858/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/26th-winners.html |archivedate=July 6, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Fred Zinnemann 1940s.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Fred Zinnemann]]; Best Director winner|alt=Fred Zinnemann 1940s.jpg]]\n[[File:WILLIAMHolden.jpg|thumb|150px|[[William Holden]]; Best Actor winner|alt=WILLIAMHolden.jpg]]\n[[File:Audrey Hepburn 1956.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Audrey Hepburn]]; Best Actress winner|alt=Audrey Hepburn 1956.jpg]]\n[[File:Frank Sinatra '57.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Frank Sinatra]]; Best Supporting Actor winner|alt=Frank Sinatra '57.jpg]]\n[[File:DOnnaREed.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Donna Reed]]; Best Supporting Actress winner]]\n[[File:Charles Brackett.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Charles Brackett]]; Best Story and Screenplay co-winner|alt=Charles Brackett.jpg]]\n[[File:Trumbo 1947.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Dalton Trumbo]]; Best Story winner|alt=Trumbo at the House Un-American Activities Committee hearings in 1947]]\n[[File:Walt Disney 1946.JPG|thumb|150px|[[Walt Disney]]; Best Animated Short Film, Best Documentary Feature, Best Documentary Short Subject and Best Live Action Short Subject, Two-Reel winner|alt=Walt Disney 1946.JPG]]\n[[File:Cedric-Gibbons-1936.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Cedric Gibbons]]; Best Art Direction, Black-and-White co-winner|alt=Cedric-Gibbons-1936.jpg]]\n[[File:Charles LeMaire.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Charles LeMaire]]; Best Costume Design, Color winner|alt=Charles LeMaire.jpg]]\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82; width:50%\" | [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Motion Picture]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82; width:50%\" | [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[From Here to Eternity]] \u2013 ''[[Buddy Adler]] for [[Columbia Pictures]]&nbsp;'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Julius Caesar (1953 film)|Julius Caesar]] \u2013 ''[[John Houseman]] for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]&nbsp; \n**''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]] \u2013 ''[[Frank Ross (producer)|Frank Ross]] for [[20th Century Fox]]&nbsp; \n**''[[Roman Holiday]] \u2013 ''[[William Wyler]] for [[Paramount Pictures]]&nbsp; \n**''[[Shane (film)|Shane]] \u2013 ''[[George Stevens]] for Paramount Pictures&nbsp; \n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''[[Fred Zinnemann]]&nbsp;\u2013 