urke/Lorene'''{{double dagger}}\n**[[Grace Kelly]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Mogambo]]'' as Linda Nordley\n**[[Geraldine Page]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Hondo (film)|Hondo]]'' as Angie Lowe\n**[[Marjorie Rambeau]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Torch Song (1953 film)|Torch Song]]'' as Mrs. Stewart\n**[[Thelma Ritter]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Pickup on South Street]]'' as Moe\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" |  [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" |  [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Story and Screenplay]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[From Here to Eternity]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Daniel Taradash]] from ''[[From Here to Eternity (novel)|From Here to Eternity]]'' by [[James Jones (author)|James Jones]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[The Cruel Sea (1953 film)|The Cruel Sea]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Eric Ambler]] from ''[[The Cruel Sea (novel)|The Cruel Sea]]'' by [[Nicholas Monsarrat]]\n**''[[Lili]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Helen Deutsch]] from \"Love of Seven Dolls\" by [[Paul Gallico]]\n**''[[Roman Holiday]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ian McLellan Hunter]] and [[John Dighton]] from a story by [[Dalton Trumbo]]\n**''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[A.B. Guthrie Jr.]] from ''[[Shane (novel)|Shane]]'' by [[Jack Schaefer]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Titanic (1953 film)|Titanic]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Charles Brackett]], [[Walter Reisch]] and [[Richard L. Breen]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[The Band Wagon]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Betty Comden]] and [[Adolph Green]]\n**''[[The Desert Rats (film)|The Desert Rats]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Richard Murphy (screenwriter)|Richard Murphy]]\n**''[[The Naked Spur]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Sam Rolfe]] and [[Harold Jack Bloom]]\n**''[[Take the High Ground!]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Millard Kaufman]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Story|Best Story]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Best Short Subject - Cartoons]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Roman Holiday]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Dalton Trumbo]]'''{{double dagger}} (awarded posthumously as Trumbo was on the [[Hollywood blacklist]])\n**''[[Above and Beyond (1952 film)|Above and Beyond]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Beirne Lay Jr.]]\n**''[[The Captain's Paradise]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Alec Coppel]]\n**''[[Hondo (film)|Hondo]]''&nbsp;\u2013  [[Louis L'Amour]] (disqualified)\n**''[[Little Fugitive (1953 film)|Little Fugitive]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ray Ashley]], [[Morris Engel]], and [[Ruth Orkin]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Toot, Whistle, Plunk and Boom]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Walt Disney]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''Christopher Crumpet''\n**''[[From A to Z-Z-Z-Z]]''\n**''[[Rugged Bear]]''\n**''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1953 American film)|The Tell Tale Heart]]''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)|Best Documentary Short Subject]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[The Living Desert]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Walt Disney]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[The Conquest of Everest]]''\n**''[[A Queen Is Crowned]]''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[The Alaskan Eskimo]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Walt Disney]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[The Living City]]''\n**''[[Operation Blue Jay]]''\n**''[[They Planted a Stone]]''\n**''[[The Word (1953 film)|The Word]]''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Live Action Short Subject, One-Reel]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Live Action Short Subject, Two-Reel]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Overture to The Merry Wives of Windsor]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Johnny Green]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''Christ Among the Primitives''\n**''[[Herring Hunt]]''\n**''Joy of Living''\n**''Wee Water Wonders''\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Bear Country (film)|Bear Country]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Walt Disney]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Ben and Me]]''\n**''[[Return to Glennascaul]]''\n**''Vesuvius Express''\n**''Winter Paradise''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Music Score of a Dramatic or Comedy Picture]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Scoring of a Musical Picture]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Lili]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bronis\u0142aw Kaper]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Above and Beyond (1952 film)|Above and Beyond]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Hugo Friedhofer]]\n**''[[From Here to Eternity]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Morris Stoloff]] and [[George Duning]]\n**''[[Julius Caesar (1953 film)|Julius Caesar]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Mikl\u00f3s R\u00f3zsa]]\n**''[[This Is Cinerama]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Louis Forbes\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Call Me Madam (film)|Call Me Madam]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Alfred Newman (composer)|Alfred Newman]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[The 5,000 Fingers of Dr. T.]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Friedrich Hollaender|Frederick Hollander]] and [[Morris Stoloff]]\n**''[[The Band Wagon]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Adolph Deutsch]]\n**''[[Calamity Jane (film)|Calamity Jane]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ray Heindorf]]\n**''[[Kiss Me Kate (film)|Kiss Me Kate]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Andr\u00e9 Previn]] and [[Saul Chaplin]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Song]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Recording]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''\"[[Secret Love (1953 song)|Secret Love]]\" from ''[[Calamity Jane (film)|Calamity Jane]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Music by [[Sammy Fain]]; Lyrics by [[Paul Francis Webster]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**\"The Moon Is Blue\" from ''[[The Moon Is Blue]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Music by [[Herschel Burke Gilbert]]; Lyrics by [[Sylvia Fine]]\n**\"My Flaming Heart\" from ''[[Small Town Girl (1953 film)|Small Town Girl]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Music by [[Nicholas Brodszky]]; Lyrics by [[Leo Robin]]\n**\"Sadie Thompson's Song\" from ''[[Miss Sadie Thompson]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Music by Lester Lee; Lyrics by [[Ned Washington]]\n**\"[[That's Amore (song)|That's Amore]]\" from ''[[The Caddy]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Music by [[Harry Warren]]; Lyrics by [[Jack Brooks (lyricist)|Jack Brooks]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[From Here to Eternity]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[John P. Livadary]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Calamity Jane (film)|Calamity Jane]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[William A. Mueller]]\n**''[[Knights of the Round Table (film)|Knights of the Round Table]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[A. W. Watkins]]\n**''[[The Mississippi Gambler (1953 film)|The Mississippi Gambler]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Leslie I. Carey]]\n**''[[The War of the Worlds (1953 film)|The War of the Worlds]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Loren L. Ryder]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction, Black-and-White]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction, Color]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Julius Caesar (1953 film)|Julius Caesar]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Cedric Gibbons]] and [[Edward Carfagno]]; Set Decoration: [[Edwin B. Willis]] and [[Hugh Hunt]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Martin Luther (1953 film)|Martin Luther]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction and Set Decoration: [[Fritz Maurischat]] and [[Paul Markwitz]]\n**''[[The President's Lady]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Lyle R. Wheeler]] and [[Leland Fuller]]; Set Decoration: [[Paul S. Fox]]\n**''[[Roman Holiday]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction and Set Decoration: [[Hal Pereira]] and [[Walter H. Tyler|Walter Tyler]]\n**''[[Titanic (1953 film)|Titanic]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Lyle R. Wheeler]] and [[Maurice Ransford]]; Set Decoration: [[Stuart A. Reiss]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Lyle R. Wheeler]] and [[George Davis (art director)|George Davis]]; Set Decoration: [[Walter M. Scott]] and [[Paul S. Fox]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Knights of the Round Table (film)|Knights of the Round Table]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Alfred Junge]] and [[Hans Peters (art director)|Hans Peters]]; Set Decoration: [[John Jarvis (set decorator)|John Jarvis]]\n**''[[Lili]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Cedric Gibbons]] and [[Paul Groesse]]; Set Decoration: [[Edwin B. Willis]] and [[Arthur Krams]]\n**''[[The Story of Three Loves]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Cedric Gibbons]], [[E. Preston Ames]], [[Edward Carfagno]] and [[Gabriel Scognamillo]]; Set Decoration: [[Edwin B. Willis]], [[F. Keogh Gleason]], [[Arthur Krams]] and [[Jack D. Moore]]\n**''[[Young Bess]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Art Direction: [[Cedric Gibbons]] and [[Urie McCleary]]; Set Decoration: [[Edwin B. Willis]] and [[Jack D. Moore]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography, Black-and-White]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography, Color]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[From Here to Eternity]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Burnett Guffey]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[The Four Poster (film)|The Four Poster]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Hal Mohr]]\n**''[[Julius Caesar (1953 film)|Julius Caesar]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Joseph Ruttenberg]]\n**''[[Martin Luther (1953 film)|Martin Luther]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Joseph C. Brun]]\n**''[[Roman Holiday]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Franz Planer]] and [[Henri Alekan]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Loyal Griggs]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[All the Brothers Were Valiant]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[George Folsey (cinematographer)|George Folsey]]\n**''[[Beneath the 12-Mile Reef]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Edward Cronjager]]\n**''[[Lili]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Robert Planck\n**''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Leon Shamroy]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design, Black-and-White]]\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design, Color]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''''[[Roman Holiday]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Edith Head]]'''{{double dagger}}\n** ''[[The Actress]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Walter Plunkett]]\n** ''[[Dream Wife]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Helen Rose]] and [[Herschel McCoy]]\n** ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Jean Louis]]\n** ''[[The President's Lady]]''&nbsp;\u2013  [[Charles LeMaire]] and [[Reni\u00e9]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* '''''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Charles LeMaire]] and [[Emile Santiago]]'''{{double dagger}}\n** ''[[The Band Wagon]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Mary Ann Nyberg]]\n** ''[[Call Me Madam (film)|Call Me Madam]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Irene Sharaff]]\n** ''[[How to Marry a Millionaire]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Charles LeMaire]] and [[William Travilla]]\n** ''[[Young Bess]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Walter Plunkett]]\n|-\n! style=\"background:#EEDD82\" | [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]]\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*'''''[[From Here to Eternity]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[William Lyon (film editor)|William Lyon]]'''{{double dagger}}\n**''[[Crazylegs (film)|Crazylegs]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Cotton Warburton|Irvine (Cotton) Warburton]]\n**''[[The Moon Is Blue]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Otto Ludwig (film editor)|Otto Ludwig]]\n**''[[Roman Holiday]]''&nbsp;\u2013 [[Robert Swink]]\n**''[[The War of the Worlds (1953 film)|The War of the Worlds]]''&nbsp;\u2013 Everett Douglas\n|}\n\n===Academy Honorary Awards===\n* [[Pete Smith (film producer)|Pete Smith]] \u2013 \"For his witty and pungent observations on the American scene in his series of 'Pete Smith Specialties{{'\"}}.\n* [[20th Century Fox|Twentieth Century-Fox Film Corporation]] \u2013 \"In recognition of their imagination, showmanship and foresight in introducing the revolutionary process known as [[CinemaScope]]\".\n* [[Joseph Breen|Joseph I. Breen]] \u2013 \"For his conscientious, open-minded and dignified management of the Motion Picture Production Code\".\n* [[Bell & Howell|Bell and Howell Company]] \u2013 \"For their pioneering and basic achievements in the advancement of the motion picture industry\".\n* ''[[The War of the Worlds (1953 film)|The War of the Worlds]]'' for [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Special Effects]].\n\n===Irving G. Thalberg Memorial Award===\n* [[George Stevens]]\n\n=== Academy Award of Merit===\n* [[Henri Chretien]] for [[Cinemascope]] contribution\n\n==Presenters and performers==\n\n===Presenters===\n*[[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Michael Wilding (actor)|Michael Wilding]] \u2013 Presenters of the Documentary Awards\n*[[Jack Webb]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Sound Recording\n*[[Keefe Brasselle]] and [[Marilyn Erskine]] \u2013 Presenters of the Short Subject Awards\n*[[Esther Williams]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Film Editing\n*[[Gene Tierney]] \u2013 Presenter of the awards for Costume Design\n*[[Gower Champion]] and [[Marge Champion]] \u2013 Presenters of the award for Art Direction\n*[[Lex Barker]] and [[Lana Turner]] \u2013 Presenters of the awards for Cinematography\n*[[Kirk Douglas]] \u2013 Presenter of the Writing awards\n*[[Irene Dunne]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Director\n*[[Walter Brennan]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Supporting Actress\n*[[Mercedes McCambridge]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Supporting Actor\n*[[Arthur Freed]] \u2013 Presenter of the Music awards\n*[[Gary Cooper]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Actress\n*[[Shirley Booth]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Actor\n*[[Cecil B. DeMille]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Motion Picture\n*[[Merle Oberon]] \u2013 Presenter of the award for Best Special Effects\n*[[Charles Brackett]] \u2013 Presenter of the Honorary Awards\n*[[Tyrone Power]] \u2013 Presenter of the Scientific & Technical Awards\n*[[David O. Selznick]] \u2013 Presenter of the Irving G. Thalberg Award\n\n===Performers===\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Previn]] \u2013 Conductor the Academy Awards orchestra\n*[[Mitzi Gaynor]] and [[Donald O'Connor]] \u2013 Performers of \"The Moon Is Blue\" from ''[[The Moon Is Blue]]''\n*[[Connie Russell]] \u2013 Performer of \"Sadie Thompson's Song (Blue Pacific Blues)\" from ''[[Miss Sadie Thompson]]''\n*[[Ann Blyth]] \u2013 Performer of \"[[Secret Love (1953 song)|Secret Love]]\" from ''[[Calamity Jane (film)|Calamity Jane]]''\n*[[Dean Martin]] \u2013 Performer of \"[[That's Amore]]\" from ''[[The Caddy]]''\n\n==Multiple nominations and awards==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-1-of-2}}\nThese films had multiple nominations:\n\n* 13 nominations: ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''\n* 10 nominations: ''[[Roman Holiday]]''\n* 6 nominations: ''[[Lili]]'' and ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]''\n* 5 nominations: ''[[Julius Caesar (1953 film)|Julius Caesar]]'' and ''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]]''\n* 3 nominations: ''[[The Band Wagon]]'', ''[[Calamity Jane (film)|Calamity Jane]]'', ''[[The Moon Is Blue]]'', ''[[Stalag 17]]'', and ''[[The War of the Worlds (1953 film)|The War of the Worlds]]''\n* 2 nominations: ''[[Above and Beyond (1952 film)|Above and Beyond]]'', ''[[Call Me Madam (film)|Call Me Madam]]'', ''[[Knights of the Round Table (film)|Knights of the Round Table]]'', ''[[Martin Luther (1953 film)|Martin Luther]]'', ''[[Mogambo]]'', ''[[The President's Lady]]'', ''[[Titanic (1953 film)|Titanic]]'', and ''[[Young Bess]]''\n\n{{Col-2-of-2}}\nThe following films received multiple awards.\n\n* 8 wins: ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''\n* 3 wins: ''[[Roman Holiday]]''\n* 2 wins: ''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]]''\n\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[11th Golden Globe Awards]]\n*[[1953 in film]]\n* [[5th Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n* [[6th Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n* [[7th British Academy Film Awards]]\n* [[8th Tony Awards]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Academy Awards Chron}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Academy Awards, 26}}\n[[Category:Academy Awards ceremonies]]\n[[Category:1953 film awards]]\n[[Category:1954 in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1954 in New York City]]\n[[Category:1954 in American cinema]]\n[[Category:March 1954 events]]\n[[Category:Events in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Lord Cornwallis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/26th_Academy_Awards"}
{"title_page": "Open-source Unicode typefaces", "text_new": "[[File:Sans-serif libre typefaces (fonts).png|thumb|alt=Screenshot of type set in several different free (libre) sans-serif typefaces: Latin Modern Sans, Liberation Sans, Arimo, FreeSans, Nimbus Sans L, Tex Gyre Heros, Droid Sans, Roboto, Noto, Bitstream Vera Sans, and DejaVu Sans.|Examples of several [[Free software|libre]], [[sans-serif]] typefaces.]]\n\nA few projects exist to provide '''free and open-source Unicode typefaces''', i.e. [[Unicode typefaces]] which are [[open-source]] and designed to contain [[glyph]]s of all [[Unicode]] characters. However, there are also numerous projects aimed at providing only a certain script, such as the [[Arabeyes]] Arabic font. The advantage of targeting only some scripts with a [[font]] was that certain Unicode characters should be rendered differently depending on which language they are used in, and that a font that only includes the characters a certain user needs will be much smaller in file size compared to one with many glyphs. Unicode fonts in modern formats such as [[OpenType]] can in theory cover multiple languages by including multiple glyphs per character, though very few actually cover more than one language's forms of the [[Han unification|unified Han characters]].\n==History==\n===GNU Unifont===\n{{Main|GNU Unifont}}\n'''[[GNU Unifont]]''' is a [[bitmap]]-based font created by Roman Czyborra that is  present in most free [[operating system]]s and windowing systems such as [[Linux]], [[XFree86]] or the [[X.Org Server]]. The font is released under the [[GNU General Public License]] Version 2+ with a font embedding exception.\n\n===Fixed===\n{{Main|Fixed (typeface)}}\nThe [[Fixed (typeface)|Fixed]] X11 public-domain core bitmap fonts have provided substantial Unicode coverage since 1997.\n\n==21st Century==\n===2000s===\n====Free UCS Outline Fonts====\n{{Main|Free UCS Outline Fonts}}\nThe '''Free UCS Outline Fonts''' <ref>[http://savannah.gnu.org/projects/freefont/ Free UCS Outline Fonts]</ref> (also known as '''freefont''') is a font collection project. The project was started by Primo\u017e Peterlin and is currently administered by Steve White.  The aim of this project has been to produce a package of fonts by collecting existing free fonts and special donations, to support as many Unicode characters as possible. The font family is released as '''GNU FreeFont''' under the [[GNU General Public License]]. It also supports several font formats, including [[PostScript]], [[TrueType]], and [[OpenType]]. For this reason the fonts are derived from original work made in [[FontForge]], and stored in .sfd (Spline Font Database) files. The most recent release is from May 2012.\n\n====SIL fonts====\n[[SIL International]] offers a large number of fonts, editors, translation and book production systems<ref>[http://scripts.sil.org/default NRSI: Computers and Writing Systems]</ref> as part of their goal to bridge the [[digital divide]] to minority languages. This site contains many utilities for Windows systems, including right-to-left editors, keymappers, RTF translators, and high-quality, free Unicode fonts.\nSIL publish their fonts under their own [[SIL Open Font License]]. Typefaces include [[Charis SIL]], [[Doulos SIL]] and [[Gentium]].\n\n====MPH 2B Damase====\nMark Williamson's MPH 2B Damase is a free font encoding many non-Latin scripts, including the Unicode 4.1 scripts in the [[Supplementary Multilingual Plane]]:\n[[Armenian alphabet|Armenian]], Cherokee, Coptic, [[Cypriot Syllabary]], [[Cyrillic]], Deseret, Georgian, [[Glagolitic]], Gothic, Greek, Hebrew, Latin, Limbu, [[Linear B]] (partial coverage), Old Italic, [[Old Persian cuneiform]], [[Osmanya]], [[Phoenician alphabet|Phoenician]], [[Shavian]], [[Syloti Nagri]] (no conjuncts), [[Tai Le (Unicode block)|Tai Le]] (no combining tone marks), [[Thaana]], [[Tifinagh]], [[Ugaritic]], and [[Vietnamese alphabet|Vietnamese]].<ref>[http://www.wazu.jp/gallery/views/View_MPH2BDamase.html Details for MPH 2B Damase]</ref>\n\n====IndUni fonts====\nThe IndUni fonts are a GPL-licensed font family with many accents and combining characters, especially suitable for Indic, Indian and Nepali (Sanskrit, Prakrit, Hindi) and Middle Eastern languages and Urdu in transliteration. It also includes characters for Avestan and for the Pinyin representation of Chinese, a set of Cyrillic characters and a basic set of Greek letters. The fonts implement almost the whole of the Multilingual European Subset 1 of Unicode. Also provided are keyboard handlers for Windows and the Mac, making input easy.\n\nThey are based on fonts designed by [[URW++]] Design and Development Incorporated, and offer lookalikes for [[Courier (typeface)|Courier]], [[Helvetica]], [[Times Roman|Times]], [[Palatino]], and [[New Century Schoolbook]].<ref>[http://bombay.indology.info/software/fonts/induni/ IndUni fonts, by John Smith]</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n==== Noto fonts ====\n{{main|Noto fonts}}\nNoto is a font family designed to cover all the scripts encoded in the [[Unicode]] standard. It is designed with the goal of achieving visual harmony (e.g., compatible heights and stroke thicknesses) across multiple languages/scripts. Commissioned by [[Google]], the font is licensed under the [[SIL Open Font License]].<ref name=\"cgc/noto\">{{cite web |title = Noto Font |url = https://github.com/googlei18n/noto-fonts/blob/master/LICENSE|accessdate = November 24, 2015 }}</ref> Until September 2015, the fonts were under the [[Apache License 2.0]].<ref>{{cite web |title =  Add NEWS for license change - googlei18n/noto-fonts |url = https://github.com/googlei18n/noto-fonts/commit/787e6b68b264428063342415d7c96afa3a32eec9|accessdate = 2016-04-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Comparison==\n<!-- Please keep this table sorted alphabetically -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Font name !!License !!Version / date !!Notes\n|-\n|[[Amiri (typeface)|Amiri Font]] ||[[SIL Open Font License|OFL]] ||0.111 (30 Dec 2017) ||