2011/05/20115228013977326.html The crucible of Yemen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025105428/http://english.aljazeera.net/indepth/opinion/2011/05/20115228013977326.html |date=25 October 2011 }}. Al Jazeera.net.</ref>\n* [[Students]]<ref>[http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=2011022520593875 YEMEN: Student protests gather strength after deaths] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224024750/http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=2011022520593875 |date=24 February 2013 }}. Universityworldnews.com (27 February 2011).</ref>\n* [[Hashid]]<ref>Associates, Menas. (24 May 2011) [http://menasassociates.blogspot.com/2011/05/yemen-hashid-tribe-clashes-with.html YEMEN: Hashid tribe clashes with security forces] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201124939/http://menasassociates.blogspot.com/2011/05/yemen-hashid-tribe-clashes-with.html |date=1 February 2016 }}. Menasassociates.blogspot.com.</ref>\n* [[Alliance of Yemeni Tribes]]<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/World/Story/STIStory_696854.html Yemeni tribes form coalition against Saleh]. ''The Straits Times''. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121084130/http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/World/Story/STIStory_696854.html |date=21 January 2012 }}</ref>\n* Defected soldiers<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-04/13/c_13827610.htm |title=10,000 Yemeni forces defect from government, join protesters: official |agency=Xinhua News Agency |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=20 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110417013728/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-04/13/c_13827610.htm |archive-date=17 April 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Civil Bloc<ref>{{cite news | author = Johnston, Cynthia | url = http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/03/24/idINIndia-55848220110324 | title = Yemen Forces Clash over Saleh Before Friday Protest | agency = Reuters | date = 24 March 201 | accessdate = 20 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120112235428/http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/03/24/idINIndia-55848220110324 | archive-date = 12 January 2012 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* National Dialogue Committee<ref>{{cite web |url=http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2010/03/20/the-yemeni-national-dialog-committee-issues-vision-for-national-salvation/ |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110203063005/http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2010/03/20/the-yemeni-national-dialog-committee-issues-vision-for-national-salvation/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 February 2011 |title=The Yemeni National Dialog Committee Issues Vision for National Salvation |publisher=Armies of Liberation |date=20 March 2010 |accessdate=20 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| side2        = {{flagicon|Yemen}} '''Yemeni government:'''\n*[[General People's Congress (Yemen)|General People's Congress]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of the Yemeni Army.svg}} [[Yemen Army]]\n*{{Flagicon image|Flag of the Yemeni Interior Ministry.svg}} [[Law enforcement in Yemen|Yemeni Police Force]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of the Yemeni Central Security Organization.svg}} [[Special Security Forces (Yemen)|Central Security Organization]]\n*{{flagicon image|Yemeni Republican Guard Flag.svg}} [[Republican Guard (Yemen)|Republican Guards]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of the Yemeni Air Force.svg}} [[Yemeni Air Force]]\n* Pro-Government Tribes\n| howmany1 =\n| howmany2 =\n| injuries     = 22,000<ref name=2,000killed>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/yemen-says-more-than-2000-killed-in-uprising/2012/03/18/gIQAGOtcLS_story.html Yemen says more than 2,000 killed in uprising] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325152038/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/yemen-says-more-than-2000-killed-in-uprising/2012/03/18/gIQAGOtcLS_story.html |date=25 March 2012 }}. ''The Washington Post''. (19 March 2012).</ref>\n| fatalities = 2,000 (by 18 March 2012)<ref name=2,000killed/>\n| arrests       = 1,000<ref>[http://bikyamasr.com/47848/yemen-report-over-1000-missing-possibly-tortured/Yemen report: Over 1,000 missing, possibly tortured]{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}},  8 November 2011</ref>\n| concessions   =\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Yemeni uprising}}\n{{Campaignbox Yemeni Crisis}}\n{{Yemeni Crisis (2011\u2013present)}}\nThe '''Yemeni Revolution''' ('''[[intifada]]'''),<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1475-4967.2011.00499.x | volume=18 | title=Yemen: A Social Intifada In a Republic of Sheikhs | year=2011 | journal=Middle East Policy | pages=79\u201385 | last1 = Fattah | first1 = Khaled}}</ref> and also known as the '''Yemeni Revolution of Dignity'''<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1215/01903659-1506283 | volume=39 | issue=1 | title=A Revolution of Dignity and Poetry | year=2012 | journal=Boundary 2 | pages=137\u2013165 | last1 = Omri | first1 = Mohamed-Salah}}</ref> followed the initial stages of the [[Tunisian Revolution]] and occurred simultaneously with the [[Egyptian Revolution of 2011]]<ref name=\"Thousands call\" /> and other [[Arab Spring|Arab Spring protests]] in the Middle East and North Africa. In its early phase, protests in [[Yemen]] were initially against unemployment, economic conditions<ref name=\"afreuters\" /> and corruption,<ref name=\"People are fed up\">\n{{cite news\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12298019\n| title = Yemen Protests: 'People Are Fed Up with Corruption'\n| work = BBC News\n| date = 27 January 2011\n| accessdate = 14 May 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190513/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12298019\n| archive-date = 5 April 2011\n| url-status = live\n| df = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> as well as against the government's proposals to modify [[constitution of Yemen|Yemen's constitution]]. The protesters' demands then escalated to calls for the resignation of [[President of Yemen|Yemeni President]] [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]]. Mass defections from the military, as well as from Saleh's government, effectively rendered much of the country outside of the government's control, and protesters vowed to defy its authority.\n\nA major demonstration of over 16,000 protesters took place in [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]], Yemen's capital, on 27 January.<ref name=\"Irish Times breaking26\" /> On 2 February, Saleh announced he would not run for reelection in 2013 and that he would not pass power to his son. On 3 February, 20,000 people protested against the government in Sana\u02bda,<ref name=\"latimes_3feb_20k\">{{cite news | author1 = Daragahi, Borzou | author2 = Browning, Noah | url = https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/middleeast/la-fg-yemen-rallies-20110204,0,7940190.story | title = Tens of Thousands Turn Out for Rival Rallies in Yemen | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = 3 February 2011 | accessdate = 29 April 2011 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120903153118/http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/03/world/la-fg-yemen-rallies-20110204 | archive-date = 3 September 2012 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"bbc_20k\" /> while others protested in [[Aden]],<ref name=\"aljaz_aden\" /> a southern Yemeni seaport city, in a \"Day of Rage\" called for by [[Tawakel Karman]],<ref name=\"Feb3_DayRage_aljaz\" /> while soldiers, armed members of the [[General People's Congress (Yemen)|General People's Congress]] and many protesters held a pro-government rally in Sana\u02bda.<ref name=\"oneindia_armedGPC_progov\" /> In a \"Friday of Anger\" on 18 February, tens of thousands of Yemenis took part in anti-government demonstrations in [[Taiz]], Sana\u02bda and Aden. On a \"Friday of No Return\" on 11 March, protesters called for Saleh's ousting in Sana\u02bda where three people were killed. More protests were held in other cities, including [[Mukalla]], where one person was killed. On 18 March, protesters in Sana\u02bda were fired upon, resulting in 52 deaths and ultimately culminating in mass defections and resignations.<ref>[http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2011/6/4/worldupdates/2011-06-04T010231Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_-574889-1&sec=Worldupdates \"Yemen president Saleh fights to keep grip on power\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716195820/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2011%2F6%2F4%2Fworldupdates%2F2011-06-04T010231Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_-574889-1&sec=Worldupdates |date=16 July 2012 }}. ''The Star'' (Malaysia).</ref>\n\nStarting in late April, Saleh agreed to a [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]-brokered deal, only to back away hours before the scheduled signing three times. After the third time, on 22 May, the GCC declared it was suspending its efforts to mediate in Yemen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/201152216373928689.html|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=22 May 2011|accessdate=23 May 2011|title=Yemen transition deal collapses|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523103754/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/201152216373928689.html|archive-date=23 May 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 23 May, a day after Saleh refused to sign the transition agreement, Sheikh [[Sadiq al-Ahmar]], the head of the [[Hashid]] tribal federation, one of the most powerful tribes in the country, declared support for the opposition and his armed supporters came into conflict with loyalist security forces in the capital Sana\u02bda. Heavy street fighting ensued, which included artillery and mortar shelling.<ref name=\"570news\">{{cite news|url=http://www.570news.com/news/world/article/231160--yemen-s-president-vows-to-resist-failed-state-as-tribes-press-offensive-against-regime |title=Yemen's president vows to resist 'failed state' as tribes press offensive against regime |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928061849/http://www.570news.com/news/world/article/231160--yemen-s-president-vows-to-resist-failed-state-as-tribes-press-offensive-against-regime |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"cnn.com\">[http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/05/25/yemen.unrest/index.html Tribal fighters occupy government buildings in Yemen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110010910/http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/05/25/yemen.unrest/index.html |date=10 November 2012 }}. CNN.</ref><ref name=\"alternet.org\">[http://www.alternet.org/rss/breaking_news/598992/us_orders_non-emergency__staff_to_leave_yemen/ Fighting grips Yemeni capital as Saleh orders arrests] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110618102916/http://www.alternet.org/rss/breaking_news/598992/us_orders_non-emergency__staff_to_leave_yemen/ |date=18 June 2011 }}. Alternet.org.</ref> Saleh and several others were injured and at least five people were killed by a 3 June bombing of the presidential compound when an explosion ripped through a mosque used by high-level government officials for prayer services.<ref name=\"palaceshell\">[http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/06/03/yemen.unrest/index.html Yemen palace shelled; sheikh, guards killed, president, PM hurt] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604172202/http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/06/03/yemen.unrest/index.html |date=4 June 2011 }}. CNN.</ref> Reports conflicted as to whether the attack was caused by shelling or a planted bomb.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mubasher.aljazeera.net/Services/System/?Rq=6%29O7AzSe8-5HrW7D2pS-6XhaCU!S%28-6GO=NEJwf-7%29rcSOa5e-4!Hbwe47|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=10 June 2011|accessdate=11 June 2011|title=40% \u0645\u0646 \u062c\u0633\u0645 \u0635\u0627\u0644\u062d \u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723191855/http://mubasher.aljazeera.net/Services/System/?Rq=6)O7AzSe8-5HrW7D2pS-6XhaCU!S(-6GO=NEJwf-7)rcSOa5e-4!Hbwe47|archive-date=23 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The next day, Vice President [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]] took over as acting president<ref>[http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/yemen-jun-4-2011-2332 Al-Hadi acting President of Yemen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127180754/http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/yemen-jun-4-2011-2332 |date=27 November 2011 }}. Al Jazeera.net (4 June 2011).</ref> while Saleh flew to [[Saudi Arabia]] to be treated. The crowds celebrated Saleh's transfer of power, but Yemeni officials insisted that Saleh's absence was temporary and he would soon return to Yemen to resume his duties of office.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle-east/speculation-grows-on-yemeni-presidents-condition/2011/06/04/AGpN9xIH_story.html Yemeni crowds celebrate after president transfers power, flies to Saudi Arabia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019123848/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle-east/speculation-grows-on-yemeni-presidents-condition/2011/06/04/AGpN9xIH_story.html |date=19 October 2017 }}. ''The Washington Post''. (5 June 2011).</ref>\n\nIn early July the government rejected the opposition's demands, including the formation of a transitional council with the goal of formally transferring power from the current administration to a [[caretaker government]] intended to oversee Yemen's first-ever democratic elections.<ref name=\"english.ntdtv.com\">{{cite news|url=http://english.ntdtv.com/ntdtv_en/news_middleeast_africa/2011-07-06/minister-says-yemen-will-not-accept-a-transitional-council.html |publisher=NTDTV |date=6 July 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2011 |title=Minister Says Yemen Will Not Accept a Transitional Council |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004225454/http://english.ntdtv.com/ntdtv_en/news_middleeast_africa/2011-07-06/minister-says-yemen-will-not-accept-a-transitional-council.html |archivedate=4 October 2011 }}</ref> In response, factions of the opposition announced the formation of their own 17-member transitional council on 16 July, though the [[Joint Meeting Parties]] that have functioned as an umbrella for many of the Yemeni opposition groups during the uprising said the council did not represent them and did not match their \"plan\" for the country.<ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/16/us-yemen-idUSTRE76F0ZP20110716|agency=Reuters|date=16 July 2011|accessdate=17 July 2011|title=Yemen protesters set up transitional council|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154224/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/16/us-yemen-idUSTRE76F0ZP20110716|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November, Saleh signed a power-transfer agreement brokered by the Gulf Cooperation Council in [[Riyadh]], under which he would transfer his power to his Vice-President, [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]], within 30 days and leave his post as president by February 2012, in exchange for immunity from prosecution.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2011/Nov-23/154953-yemens-saleh-signs-deal-to-quit-power.ashx#axzz1eXuReO4L Yemen's Saleh signs deal to quit power] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720122441/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Middle-East/2011/Nov-23/154953-yemens-saleh-signs-deal-to-quit-power.ashx#axzz1eXuReO4L |date=20 July 2013 }}. ''Daily Star'' (Lebanon) (23 November 2011).</ref><ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/11/2011112355040101606.html Yemen leader signs power-transfer deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720014429/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/11/2011112355040101606.html |date=20 July 2013 }}. Al Jazeera.</ref> Although the GCC deal was accepted by the JMP, it was rejected by many of the protesters and the [[Houthis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yobserver.com/front-page/10021706.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105161736/http://www.yobserver.com/front-page/10021706.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-05 |title=Process of withdrawing troops and armed tribesmen started for enhancing peace and normalizing life in Yemen |publisher=Yobserver.com |accessdate=2012-11-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9007278114 |title=Fars News Agency :: Houthis' Leader: US, Allies Plot to Spark Sectarian Rift in Yemen |publisher=English.farsnews.com |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=2012-11-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601051013/http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9007278114 |archivedate=1 June 2012 }}</ref> A [[2012 Yemeni presidential election|presidential election]] was held in [[Yemen]] on 21 February 2012, with Hadi running unopposed. A report claims that the election had a 65% turnout, with Hadi receiving 99.8% of the vote. Hadi took the oath of office in Yemen's parliament on 25 February 2012. Saleh returned home on the same day to attend Hadi's inauguration.<ref name=nytnewpres>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/world/middleeast/abed-rabu-mansour-hadi-sworn-in-as-yemens-new-president.html|accessdate=15 August 2012|work=The New York Times|title=Yemen Swears in New President to the Sound of Applause, and Violence|first=Laura|last=Kasinof|date=27 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110144120/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/world/middleeast/abed-rabu-mansour-hadi-sworn-in-as-yemens-new-president.html|archive-date=10 November 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After months of protests, Saleh had resigned from the presidency and formally transferred power to his successor, marking the end of his 33-year rule.<ref name=\"google.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iqhKKOqo6XDujeTI_yaD4B0CcyVA?docId=CNG.12cc0199ecc6457c2d2a25874218f73d.691 |title=AFP: Yemen's Saleh formally steps down after 33 years |publisher=Google |date=27 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-11-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525115035/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iqhKKOqo6XDujeTI_yaD4B0CcyVA?docId=CNG.12cc0199ecc6457c2d2a25874218f73d.691 |archivedate=25 May 2012 }}</ref>\n{{Politics of Yemen}}\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|1994 civil war in Yemen}}\n[[File:Ali Abdullah Saleh 2004.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ali Abdullah Saleh]] had been [[President of Yemen]] from 1990 to 2012, and President of [[North Yemen]] from 1978 to 1990]]\nYemen has the fourth lowest [[Human Development Index]] ratings in the [[Arab world]] after [[Sudan]], [[Djibouti]] and [[Mauritania]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/media/HDR_2010_EN_Table1_reprint.pdf |title=Human Development Index and its components |publisher=Hdr.undp.org |accessdate=2012-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612080349/http://hdr.undp.org/en/media/HDR_2010_EN_Table1_reprint.pdf |archive-date=12 June 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt is also facing a [[Yemeni al-Qaeda crackdown|conflict]] with [[al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] as well as a revolt from [[South Yemen insurgency|South Yemen secessionists]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-01/18/c_13694992.htm |title=Al-Qaida Gunmen Assassinate Top Security Officer in South Yemen |agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=18 January 2011 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107143611/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-01/18/c_13694992.htm |archive-date=7 November 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> who want to see the old [[South Yemen]] reconstituted. There is also a [[Shia insurgency in Yemen|Shia rebellion]] by [[Zaidiyyah|Zaidi]] rebels, known as the [[Houthis]].\n\nBefore his ouster, [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]] had been Yemen's president for more than 30 years,<ref name=\"Thousands call\">\n{{cite news\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12295864\n| title = Yemen Protests: Thousands Call on President to Leave\n| work = BBC News\n| date = 27 January 2011\n| access-date = 21 June 2018\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180711200522/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12295864\n| archive-date = 11 July 2018\n| url-status = live\n| df = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> and many believed his son [[Ahmed Saleh]] was being groomed to eventually [[Dynasty|replace]] him.<ref name=\"Abigail Fielding-Smith\">\n{{cite news\n| url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/933ca0c4-29f6-11e0-997c-00144feab49a.html#axzz1CGsS8nPg\n| title= Yemenis Call for an End to Saleh Regime\n| author= Fielding-Smith, Abigail\n| work= [[Financial Times]]\n| date= 27 January 2011\n| access-date= 27 January 2011\n| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110128165732/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/933ca0c4-29f6-11e0-997c-00144feab49a.html#axzz1CGsS8nPg\n| archive-date= 28 January 2011\n| url-status= live\n| df= dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\nAlmost half of the population of Yemen lives below the poverty line, and one-third suffer from chronic hunger.<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite news| url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ym.html| title = The World Factbook: Yemen| work = [[The CIA World Factbook]]| date = 23 June 2014| accessdate = 11 April 2015| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110304220439/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ym.html| archive-date = 4 March 2011| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"tom finn\" /> Yemen ranks 146th in the [[Transparency International]] 2010 [[Corruption Perceptions Index]],<ref name=\"2010 Corruption Perceptions Index\">\n{{cite web\n| url= http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2010/results\n| title= 2010 Corruption Perceptions Index\n| publisher= [[Transparency International]]\n| year= 2010\n| access-date= 27 January 2011\n| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110804100839/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2010/results\n| archive-date= 4 August 2011\n| url-status= live\n| df= dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> and 8th in the 2012 [[List of countries by Failed States Index|Failed States Index]]<ref name=\"Failed States 2011\">{{cite web|title=The Failed States Index 2012|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/failed_states_index_2012_interactive|work=Foreign Policy|accessdate=7 November 2012|date=20 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528161748/http://www.foreignpolicy.com/failed_states_index_2012_interactive|archive-date=28 May 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  (up two places from 2010).<ref name=\"Failed States List 2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fundforpeace.org/web/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=452&Itemid=900 |title=Failed States Index Scores 2010 |publisher=[[Fund for Peace]] |year=2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703133025/http://www.fundforpeace.org/web/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=452&Itemid=900 |archivedate=3 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nA draft amendment to the [[constitution of Yemen]] was under discussion in parliament despite opposition protests. The amendment seeks to allow Saleh to remain in the office of president for life. He urged the opposition to take part in an election on 27 April to avoid \"political suicide.\"\n\nThe current parliament's mandate was extended by two years after an agreement in February 2009 agreement the ruling [[General People's Congress (Yemen)|General People's Congress]] and opposition parties seeking a dialogue on political reforms such as: moving from a presidential system to a proportional representation parliamentary system and a more [[federalism|decentralised]] government. Neither measure has been implemented.<ref name=\"aljaz_karman_detained\">{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/01/2011129112626339573.html|title=New protests erupt in Yemen|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=1 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129162342/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/01/2011129112626339573.html|archive-date=29 January 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2009 alleged internal governmental dissent===\nAccording to a [[WikiLeaks]] report released 31 January 2011, in December 2009 [[United States]] diplomat Angie Bryan claimed that there had been opposition to Saleh from his closest advisors for several months. Bryan wrote, \"Like other Saleh watchers, xxxxx<ref name=\"why_xxxxx\">Names hidden by [[WikiLeaks]] and [[United States diplomatic cables leak|collaborating newspapers]].</ref> characterizes the multitude of threats facing Saleh as qualitatively different and more threatening to the regime's stability than those during any other time in Yemen's history. 'Saleh is overwhelmed, exhausted by the war, and more and more intolerant of internal criticism. Saudi involvement comes at just the right time for him' xxxxx said. Largely unprecedented criticism of Saleh's leadership within the rarified circle of Saleh's closest advisors has increased in recent months, even including longtime Saleh loyalists such as Office of the Presidency aides xxxxx, according to xxxxx. These names add to the growing chorus of Saleh loyalists that have shed their traditional aversion to disparaging the man they call 'The Boss'\".<ref name=\"09SANAA2279\">{{cite journal | last=Bryan | first=Angie | title=Yemeni tribal leader: for Saleh, Saudi involvement in Sa'ada comes not a moment too soon | id={{WikiLeaks cable|09SANAA2279}} | publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] | date=28 December 2009 | url=http://wikileaks.ch/cable/2009/12/09SANAA2279.html | accessdate=31 January 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231213147/http://www.wikileaks.ch/cable/2009/12/09SANAA2279.html | archivedate=31 December 2010 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{main|Timeline of the Yemeni revolution}}\n\n===Protests===\n[[File:Yemen Protests 21-Feb-2011 P01.JPG|thumb|Some of the Yemeni protests at [[Sana'a University|Sana\u02bda University]] demanding dissolution of current ruling party and calling the president to resign.]]\n{{External media\n| video1 = {{YouTube|8kZ4x3-oogY|Raw Video: Yemeni Forces Open Fire on Protesters}}\n}}\nIn January 2011, shortly after the [[Tunisian revolution|popular ouster]] of the [[Tunisia]]n government, major street protests materialized in [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]], the Yemeni capital, to demand governmental changes.<ref name=\"NADA BAKRI\">{{cite news| author = Bakri, Nada| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/28/world/middleeast/28yemen.html| title = Thousands in Yemen Protest Against the Government| work = [[The New York Times]]| date = 27 January 2011| accessdate = 27 January 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161109131203/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/28/world/middleeast/28yemen.html| archive-date = 9 November 2016| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Protests spread to the traditionally restive south, with particularly aggressive protests in cities like [[Aden]] and [[Ta'izz]].<ref name=\"NADA BAKRI\" /> Initially, demonstrators protested against a plan to amend the [[constitution of Yemen|constitution]] and over the country's sluggish economy and high jobless rates.<ref name=\"afreuters\">{{cite news |author1=Ghobari, Mohammed |author2=Sudam, Mohamed |title=Update 1&nbsp;\u2013 Protests Erupt in Yemen, President Offers Reform |date=20 January 2011 |agency=Reuters |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/tunisiaNews/idAFLDE70J2BZ20110120 |accessdate=14 May 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122160117/http://af.reuters.com/article/tunisiaNews/idAFLDE70J2BZ20110120?sp=true |archivedate=22 January 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, protests grew larger by late January and took on an increasingly pointed tone of criticism toward President [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], with many demonstrators beginning to call openly for new leadership in [[Yemen]].<ref name=\"Irish Times breaking26\">{{cite news| url = https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/0127/breaking26.html| title = Yemenis in Anti-President Protest| agency = Reuters| work = The Irish Times| date = 27 January 2011| accessdate = 14 May 2011| archive-url = https://archive.today/20121204140648/http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/0127/breaking26.html| archive-date = 4 December 2012| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> including at least 10,000 at [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]] University.<ref name=\"Irish Times breaking26\" /><ref name=\"tom finn\">{{cite news| url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jan/27/yemen-protests-president-saleh| title = Yemenis Take to the Streets Calling for President Saleh To Step Down| author = Finn, Tom| work = [[The Guardian]]| date = 27 January 2011| accessdate = 14 May 2011| location = London| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130921014001/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jan/27/yemen-protests-president-saleh| archive-date = 21 September 2013| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBy February, opposition leader [[Tawakel Karman]] called for a \"Day of Rage\" in the mold of mass nationwide demonstrations that helped to topple the government of [[Tunisia]] and [[2011 Egyptian revolution|put pressure]] on the government of President [[Hosni Mubarak]] in [[Egypt]].<ref name=\"Feb3_DayRage_aljaz\">{{cite news| title = New Protests Erupt in Yemen| date=29 January 2011 |publisher=Al Jazeera | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/01/2011129112626339573.html | accessdate=29 April 2011 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110129162342/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/01/2011129112626339573.html |archivedate=29 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The protest drew more than 20,000 participants, as well as a show of force from Saleh's supporters.<ref name=\"bbc_20k\">{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12353479 | title = Yemen Protests: 20,000 Call for President Saleh To Go | work = BBC News | date = 29 January 2011 | accessdate = 29 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110203235654/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12353479 | archive-date = 3 February 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"oneindia_armedGPC_progov\">{{cite news | url = http://news.oneindia.in/2011/02/03/salehpartisans-take-over-yemen-protestsite-aid0126.html | title = Saleh Partisans Take Over Yemen Protest Site | agency = [[Agence France-Presse]] | work = OneIndia | date = 3 February 2011 | accessdate = 29 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110213101628/http://news.oneindia.in/2011/02/03/salehpartisans-take-over-yemen-protestsite-aid0126.html | archive-date = 13 February 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Security forces responded to protests in Aden with live ammunition and [[tear gas]].<ref name=\"aljaz_aden\">{{cite web| url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/201123105140512715.html| title=Opposing Protesters Rally in Yemen| publisher=Al Jazeera| date=3 February 2011| accessdate=29 April 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204075012/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/201123105140512715.html| archive-date=4 February 2011| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref> After Mubarak quit power in Egypt, demonstrators celebrating the revolution and calling for a similar uprising in Yemen were attacked by police and pro-Saleh tribesmen.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/201121211858966496.html | title = Thousands Rally Across Yemen | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 14 February 2011 | accessdate = 30 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190246/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/201121211858966496.html | archive-date = 5 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Cleric]]s called for a [[national unity government]] and elections to be held in six months in an effort to quell violence and place members of the opposition in government.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/2011217991104240.html | title = Yemen Clerics Urge Unity Government | date = 18 February 2011 | publisher = Al Jazeera | accessdate = 30 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190256/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/2011217991104240.html | archive-date = 5 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Later in the month, deaths were reported in Ta'izz and Aden after security forces attacked protesters with lethal force.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12507889 | title = Yemen Protests: Five Killed at Anti-Government Rallies | work = BBC News | date = 18 February 2011 | accessdate = 30 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110512091737/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12507889 | archive-date = 12 May 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/2011218111854417798.html | title = Yemen Observes 'Friday of Fury' | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 18 February 2011 | accessdate = 30 April 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190302/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/2011218111854417798.html | archive-date = 5 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> By the end of February, several major tribes in Yemen had joined the anti-government protests and protests swelled in size to well over 100,000 on several days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/167110.html |title=Major Tribes Join Yemen Protests |publisher=[[Press TV]] |date=26 February 2011 |accessdate=5 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302093207/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/167110.html |archivedate=2 March 2011 }}</ref> Saleh also called for a national unity government, but opposition leaders rejected the proposal and called for Saleh to step down immediately.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/2011228204148506367.html | title = Yemen Opposition Rejects Unity Deal | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 28 February 2011 | accessdate = 5 May 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190332/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/2011228204148506367.html | archive-date = 5 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn March, opposition groups presented a proposal that would see Saleh leave power peacefully,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.mysinchew.com/node/54144 | title = Yemen Opposition, Clerics Offer Saleh Smooth Exit | agency = [[Agence France-Presse]] | work = Sin Chew Daily | date = 3 March 2011 | accessdate = 18 May 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110714144130/http://www.mysinchew.com/node/54144 | archive-date = 14 July 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{registration required|date=May 2011}} {{cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/27989d86-4513-11e0-80e7-00144feab49a.html | title = Yemeni Proposition Offers Saleh a Transition Plan | work = [[Financial Times]] | date = 2 March 2011 | accessdate = 11 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110305233845/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/27989d86-4513-11e0-80e7-00144feab49a.html | archive-date = 5 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> but Saleh refused to accept it.<ref>{{cite news | title = Yemen Rallies Grow; Saleh Rejects Transition Plan | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/yemen_protests/2328432.html | agency = Reuters | publisher = [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] | date = 4 March 2011 | accessdate = 18 May 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629195544/http://www.rferl.org/content/yemen_protests/2328432.html | archive-date = 29 June 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> A number of prominent [[Yemeni government]] officials resigned over the violence used to disperse protests.<ref>{{cite news| title = Yemen MPs Quit Ruling Party| publisher = Al Jazeera| url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/20113514455840795.html| date = 5 March 2011| accessdate = 20 May 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190400/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/20113514455840795.html| archive-date = 5 April 2011| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> On 18 March 45 protesters were shot dead in Sana\u02bda,<ref>{{cite news | title = Doctors in Yemen Have Told the BBC That Unidentified Gunmen Fired on an Anti-Government Rally in the Capital, Sanaa | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/world-middle-east-12789220 | accessdate = 18 March 2011 | work = BBC News | date = 18 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405194926/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/world-middle-east-12789220 | archive-date = 5 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news | title = Yemen Forces 'Open Fire on Protesters' | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12783585 | work = BBC News | date = 18 March 2011 | accessdate = 18 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110318131151/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12783585 | archive-date = 18 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> an incident that prompted the declaration of a state of emergency<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> and international condemnation.<ref name=\"wpost18march\">{{cite news | author = Almasmar, Hakim | title = Yemen Imposes State of Emergency after Deadly Attack on Protesters | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/protesters-killed-in-yemens-capital-by/2011/03/18/ABFd2hp_story.html | accessdate = 19 March 2011 | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = 18 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121112085923/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/protesters-killed-in-yemens-capital-by/2011/03/18/ABFd2hp_story.html | archive-date = 12 November 2012 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = France Strongly Condemns Yemen Attack on Protesters | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/18/yemen-france-idUSPISIEE78520110318 | accessdate = 19 March 2011 | agency = Reuters | date = 18 March 2011 | author = Love, Brian | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110921040109/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/03/18/yemen-france-idUSPISIEE78520110318 | archive-date = 21 September 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Several days later, Saleh indicated that he would be willing to leave power by the end of the year or even sooner,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/World/20110322/yemen-saleh-out-by-year-end-110322/ | title = Yemen Leader Says Ready To Step Down by Year-End | publisher = [[CTV News Channel (Canada)|CTV News]] | date = 22 March 2011 | accessdate = 22 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110401181341/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/World/20110322/yemen-saleh-out-by-year-end-110322/ | archive-date = 1 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Jamjoom, Mohammed | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/03/23/yemen.protests/index.html | title = Yemen's Leader Says He Will Accept Transition Plan | publisher = CNN | date = 23 March 2011 | accessdate = 25 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110324152616/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/03/23/yemen.protests/index.html | archive-date = 24 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> but he later affirmed that he would not step down.<ref name=aje0325>{{cite news | title = Thousands in Yemen March Against Saleh | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201132511732578174.html | accessdate = 25 March 2011 | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 25 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110326110257/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201132511732578174.html | archive-date = 26 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = I Can't Quit, Says Yemen Leader | url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5i0TETypz8_hEMkbRK_bibXB4UTJQ?docId=N0211441301031249982A | accessdate = 25 March 2011 | date = 25 March 2011 | agency= Associated Press|work=[[Press Association|UKPA]]}}{{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = In Yemen, a Day of Rival Demonstrations | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/03/25/yemen.unrest/ | accessdate = 25 March 2011 | publisher = CNN | date = 25 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121024041722/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/03/25/yemen.unrest/ | archive-date = 24 October 2012 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> By the end of March, six of Yemen's 18 [[administrative divisions of Yemen|governorates]] were out of the government's control, officials said.<ref>{{cite news | title = Yemen Govt Loses Control of Six of the 18 Provinces | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/Yemen-govt-loses-control-of-six-of-the-18-provinces/Article1-679119.aspx | accessdate = 29 March 2011 | publisher = [[Press Trust of India]] (via [[Hindustan Times]]) | date = 29 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110504140715/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Yemen-govt-loses-control-of-six-of-the-18-provinces/Article1-679119.aspx | archive-date = 4 May 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Mediation attempts===\n{{main|Yemeni revolution reconciliation attempts}}\nIn April, the [[Gulf Co-operation Council]] attempted to mediate an end to the crisis, drafting several proposals for a transition of power. Toward the end of the month, Saleh signaled he would accept a plan that would see him leave power one month after signing and provided for a national unity government in the lead-up to elections.<ref>Hatem, Mohammed; Carey, Glen (23 April 2011).  [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-23/yemen-s-saleh-agrees-to-step-down-in-exchange-for-immunity-official-says.html \"Yemen\u2019s Saleh Agrees to Step Down in Exchange for Immunity, Official Says\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813161300/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-23/yemen-s-saleh-agrees-to-step-down-in-exchange-for-immunity-official-says.html |date=13 August 2011 }}. [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]. Retrieved 5 May 2011.</ref> By the end of the month, though, Saleh reversed course and the government announced he would not sign it, putting the GCC initiative on hold.<ref>Staff (30 April 2011).  [http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/04/201143094747158908.html \"Reports: Saleh Refuses To Sign Exit Deal\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430104841/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/04/201143094747158908.html |date=30 April 2011 }}. [[Al Jazeera]]. Retrieved 5 May 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/2011519455413402.html | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 1 May 2011 | accessdate = 2 May 2011 | title = Saleh Refusal Forces Yemen Deal Postponement | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110501103858/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/2011519455413402.html | archive-date = 1 May 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn early May, officials again indicated that Saleh would sign the GCC deal, and the opposition agreed to sign as well if Saleh signed it personally in his capacity as president.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Xinhua News Agency|date=6 May 2011|accessdate=6 May 2011|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-05/06/c_13860901.htm|title=Yemen's president, opposition to sign GCC power-transition deal in Sanaa: ministry|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509145410/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-05/06/c_13860901.htm|archive-date=9 May 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, Saleh again backed away, saying the deal did not require his signature, and the opposition followed suit, accusing Saleh of negotiating in bad faith.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/201156111244659925.html | title = Saleh 'resists' as Thousands Rally in Yemen | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 6 May 2011 | accessdate = 13 May 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110513092518/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/201156111244659925.html | archive-date = 13 May 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Protests and violence across the country intensified in the wake of this second reversal by Saleh.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle-east/13_reported_dead_after_yemeni_forces_open_fire_on_protesters/2011/05/11/AFvL7csG_story.html | title = 13 Reported Dead after Yemeni Forces Open Fire on Protesters | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = 24 March 2011 | accessdate = 13 May 2011 | first = Joel | last = Greenberg | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160307233243/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle-east/13_reported_dead_after_yemeni_forces_open_fire_on_protesters/2011/05/11/AFvL7csG_story.html | archive-date = 7 March 2016 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/201151114938490911.html |title=Several Protesters Killed in Yemen Cities |publisher=Al Jazeera |accessdate=13 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513072509/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/05/201151114938490911.html |archive-date=13 May 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn late May, opposition leaders received assurances that Saleh would sign the GCC plan after all, and they signed the deal the day before the president was scheduled to ink it as well.<ref>{{Cite news|agency=Xinhua|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-05/22/c_13887312.htm|title=Yemeni opposition signs the Gulf-brokered deal|date=22 May 2011|accessdate=23 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525222612/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-05/22/c_13887312.htm|archive-date=25 May 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Saleh however once again decided not to sign, and a brief but tense standoff occurred on 22 May when Saleh's supporters surrounded the embassy building of the [[United Arab Emirates]] in Sana\u02bda, trapping international diplomats (including the secretary-general of the GCC) inside until the government dispatched a helicopter to ferry them to the presidential palace.<ref>[http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/05/22/150031.html Saleh Gunmen Hold Many Envoys Hostage At Uae Embassy In Sana\u2019A] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525052422/http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/05/22/150031.html |date=25 May 2011 }}. Al Arabiya (22 May 2011).</ref>\n\n===Uprising===\n{{main|Battle of Sana'a (2011)}}\n[[File:Yemen division 2011-10-23.svg|thumb|Territory and areas of influence for rebels (blue) and Islamists (red) in Yemen's uprising, as of 23 October 2011.]]\n\nOn 23 May, a day after Saleh refused to sign the transition agreement, Sheikh [[Sadiq al-Ahmar]], the head of the [[Hashid]] tribal federation, one of the most powerful tribes in the country, declared support for the opposition and his armed supporters came into conflict with loyalist security forces in the capital [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]] after Saleh ordered al-Ahmar's arrest.<ref name=\"570news\"/> Heavy street fighting ensued, which included artillery and mortar shelling.<ref name=\"570news\"/><ref name=\"cnn.com\"/><ref name=\"alternet.org\"/> The militiamen had surrounded and blocked off several government buildings in the capital<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/english/news/middle-east/in-transition/Renewed-Yemen-Clashes-Leave-at-Least-Seven-Dead-122497914.html Yemeni Tribesmen Take Control of Government Buildings in Sana'a] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525195243/http://www.voanews.com/english/news/middle-east/in-transition/Renewed-Yemen-Clashes-Leave-at-Least-Seven-Dead-122497914.html |date=25 May 2011 }}. Voice of America.</ref> and people on the ground were reporting that it looked like the situation was deteriorating into a civil war.<ref>[http://www.watoday.com.au/world/yemen-on-the-brink-of-civil-war-20110524-1f1l1.html Yemen on the brink of civil war]. Watoday.com.au.</ref>\n\nAs the situation in [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]] was developing, about 300 [[Islamic terrorism|Islamist militants]] attacked and captured the coastal city of [[Zinjibar]] (population 20,000) (see [[Battle of Zinjibar]]). During the takeover of the town, the militants killed seven soldiers, including a colonel, and one civilian. Two more soldiers were killed in clashes with militants in [[Lawdar]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20120907142958/http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=690711&publicationSubCategoryId=200 Al-Qaida kills 5 policemen in S. Yemen]. Philstar.com (30 May 2011).</ref><ref>[http://www.france24.com/en/20110529-suspected-al-qaeda-militants-seize-yemeni-town-zinjibar%20 Suspected al Qaeda militants seize Yemeni town] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325131519/http://www.france24.com/en/20110529-suspected-al-qaeda-militants-seize-yemeni-town-zinjibar%20 |date=25 March 2013 }}. France 24.com (29 May 2011).</ref>\n\nOn day three of the fighting, military units that defected to the opposition were hit for the first time by mortar fire killing three soldiers and wounding 10.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110928061849/http://www.570news.com/news/world/article/231160--yemen-s-president-vows-to-resist-failed-state-as-tribes-press-offensive-against-regime Yemen's president vows to resist 'failed state' as tribes press offensive against regime]</ref> By the evening, it was reported that tribesmen took control of the Interior Ministry building, SABA state news agency, and the national airline building.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13544243 Yemen: Anti-Saleh Hashid rebels seize public buildings] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107021729/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13544243 |date=7 November 2018 }}. BBC (26 May 2011).</ref>\n\nA ceasefire was announced late on 27 May, by al-Ahmar,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-05/27/c_13897885.htm |title=Yemeni armed tribesmen announces ceasefire with gov't forces |agency=Xinhua News Agency |date=27 May 2011 |accessdate=2012-11-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107205422/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-05/27/c_13897885.htm |archive-date=7 November 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the next day, a truce was established.<ref>[http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20110819040702/http://www.france24.com/en/20110528-yemen-mediators-work-consolidate-sanaa-truce Yemen mediators work to consolidate Sanaa truce]</ref>\n\nOpposition demonstrators had occupied the main square of [[Taiz|Ta'izz]] since the start of the uprising against the rule of president Saleh. The protests were for the most part peaceful. However, that changed on 29 May, when the military started an operation to crush the protests and clear the demonstrators from their camp at the square. Troops reportedly fired live ammunition and from water cannons on the protesters, burned their tents and bulldozers ran over some of them. The opposition described the event as a massacre.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13592935 Yemen forces 'kill 20 protesters' in Taiz] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107011049/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13592935 |date=7 November 2018 }}. BBC (30 May 2011).</ref> (see 2011 [[Ta'izz clashes]])\n\nHowever, by 31 May, the ceasefire had broken down and street fighting continued in [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13599828 \"Yemen unrest: UN says 50 killed in Taiz since Sunday\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107001753/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13599828 |date=7 November 2018 }}. BBC (31 May 2011).</ref> Tribesmen had taken control of both the headquarters of the ruling [[General People's Congress (Yemen)]] and the main offices of the water utility.<ref>[http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/deadly-clashes-in-yemeni-cities-as-troops-kill-7-20110531-1feb4.html Deadly clashes in Yemeni cities as troops kill 7]. ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. (31 May 2011).</ref>\n\nOn 1 June, units of the loyalist Presidential Guard, commanded by one of Saleh's sons, shelled the headquarters of an army brigade belonging to the defected 1st Armored Division, even though the defected military units were holding a neutral position in the conflict between the loyalists and the tribesmen. The worst of the fighting was in the northern Hassaba neighborhood, where tribal fighters seized a number of government ministries and buildings. Government artillery fire heavily damaged the house of al-Ahmar and the government cut the area's electricity and water supplies. The government units, led by one of Saleh's sons, and loyalist special forces attacked but failed to recapture the Hassaba administrative building. Tribal fighters also seized the office of the General Prosecutor in the city's northwest. They were backed up by two armored vehicles from the 1st Armored Division. The Interior Ministry stated that the tribesmen had also captured a five-story building in the pro-Saleh Hadda neighborhood.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110604131907/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5ijEmHA2z43gq3RNjiWfRY94J2nwA?docId=3e4ceb37a4a7464284bb0a86f4773a2e Street battles in Yemeni capital leave 41 dead]</ref> During the 24 hours since the breakdown of the ceasefire, 47 people were killed on both sides during the heavy street fighting,<ref>[http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/airport-shuts-as-fighting-rages-in-yemen-20110602-1fh0v.html Airport shuts as fighting rages in Yemen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918144028/http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/airport-shuts-as-fighting-rages-in-yemen-20110602-1fh0v.html |date=18 September 2012 }}. ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. (2 June 2011).</ref> including 15 tribesmen<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/06/01/yemen.unrest/index.html Source: Missiles strike at Yemeni defectors' compound] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110144336/http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/06/01/yemen.unrest/index.html |date=10 November 2012 }}. CNN.</ref> and 14 soldiers.<ref>[http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE73L1PP20110601 Explosions and street fighting grip Yemen capital] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329065253/http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCATRE73L1PP20110601 |date=29 March 2012 }}. Ca.reuters.com (1 June 2011).</ref>\n\n===Presidential Palace assassination attempt===\nOn 3 June, a bombing at the presidential palace left Saleh injured and seven other top government officials wounded. Saleh, the prime minister, the deputy prime minister, the parliament chief, the governor of Sana\u02bda and a presidential aide were wounded while they were praying at a mosque inside the palace compound. Saleh was initially said to be injured in the neck and treated on the scene; later reports indicated his wounds were far more severe \u2013 including a collapsed lung and burns over 40% of his body.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mohammed |last=Jamjoom |first2=Hakim |last2=Almasmari |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/06/07/yemen.unrest/ |title=Witnesses: Tribal fighters take over major city in Yemen |publisher=CNN |date=8 June 2011 |accessdate=2011-06-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610030712/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/06/07/yemen.unrest/ |archive-date=10 June 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Four presidential guards<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121023083605/http://www.deseretnews.com/m/article/700141205 Yemen president wounded as tribesmen strike palace]. ''Deseret News''. (3 June 2011).</ref> and Sheikh Ali Mohsen al-Matari, an imam at the mosque, were killed.<ref name=\"palaceshell\"/>\n[[File:Yemeni Protests 4-Apr-2011 P01.JPG|thumb|left|Protesters in [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]].]]\nAs Saleh flew to the Saudi capital of [[Riyadh]] for surgery on 4 June, a cease-fire was brokered by Saudi Arabia's King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|Abdullah]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Yemen Truce Frays Amid Doubt Over Leader's Return| url = http://www.kclu.org/npr/?id=137002963| access-date = 9 June 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110928151501/http://www.kclu.org/npr/?id=137002963| archive-date = 28 September 2011| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Vice President [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi|Abdrabbuh Mansur al-Hadi]] took over as acting president and supreme commander of the [[Republic of Yemen Armed Forces|Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite news  | title = Wounded Yemeni president in Saudi Arabia  | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/06/201164164346765100.html  | access-date = 9 June 2011  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607034358/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/06/201164164346765100.html  | archive-date = 7 June 2011  | url-status = live  | df = dmy-all  }}</ref> Despite the ceasefire, sporadic violence continued in the capital.<ref>{{cite news| title = Clashes erode Yemen cease-fire amid power vacuum| url = http://hosted2.ap.org/APDefault/*/Article_2011-06-06-ML-Yemen/id-895adeb00ee14e36a84c82e08dda14f1| access-date = 9 June 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120906235500/http://hosted2.ap.org/APDefault/*/Article_2011-06-06-ML-Yemen/id-895adeb00ee14e36a84c82e08dda14f1| archive-date = 6 September 2012| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Saleh's powerful sons also remained in Yemen instead of traveling to Saudi Arabia with their father.<ref>{{cite news | title=Yemeni president arrives in Saudi Arabia as truce breaks in capital | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jun/05/yemeni-president-saudi-arabia | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Peter | last=Beaumont | date=5 June 2011 | access-date=13 December 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305233626/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jun/05/yemeni-president-saudi-arabia | archive-date=5 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 6 the government rejected the opposition's demands, including the formation of a transitional council with the goal of formally transferring power from the current administration to a caretaker government intended to oversee Yemen's [[2012 Yemeni presidential election|first-ever democratic election]].<ref name=\"english.ntdtv.com\"/> In response, factions of the opposition announced the formation of their own 17-member transitional council on 16 July, though the [[Joint Meeting Parties]] that functioned as an umbrella for many of the Yemeni opposition groups during the uprising said the council did not represent them and did not match their \"plan\" for the country.<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/>\n\nOn 6 August Saleh left the hospital in Saudi Arabia, but he did not return to Yemen.<ref>Al Jazeera Yemen Live Blog. [http://blogs.aljazeera.net/liveblog/yemen-aug-7-2011-0935|Sunday, August 7, 2011 \u2013 09:35 Entry]</ref>\n\nOn 18 September troops loyal to president Saleh opened fire on protesters in Sana'a, killing at least 26 people and injuring hundreds. Witnesses said security forces and armed civilians opened fire on protesters who left Change Square, where they had camped since February demanding regime change, and marched towards the city centre. Earlier on that day, government troops fired mortars into Al-Hasaba district in Sana'a, home to opposition tribal chief Sheik [[Sadeq al-Ahmar]] who claimed his fighters did not return fire after they were shelled by the Republican Guard.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/2011918141553217505.html Dozens of protesters shot dead in Yemen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925043339/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/2011918141553217505.html |date=25 September 2011 }}. Al Jazeera.net.</ref>\n\nOn 19 September snipers in nearby buildings again opened fire on Monday at peaceful demonstrators and passers-by in the capital's Change Square, killing at least 28 people and wounded more than 100. Additional deaths were reported in the southwestern city of [[Taiz]], where two people were killed and 10 were injured by gunfire from Saleh loyalists. Abdu al-Janadi, Yemen's deputy information minister, rejected accusations that the government had planned attacks on the protesters, and accused what he described as \"unknown assailants\" of carrying out the acts.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/201191913558115259.html Death toll soars in Yemen violence] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926125007/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/201191913558115259.html |date=26 September 2011 }}. Al Jazeera.net.</ref> On 19 September protesters and ex-soldiers stormed a base of the elite Republican Guards, who are loyal to the president. Reports said not a single shot was fired as the Guards fled the base, leaving their weapons behind.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/20119201429637417.html Yemeni toll rises after fresh Sanaa shelling] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926125013/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/20119201429637417.html |date=26 September 2011 }}. Al Jazeera.net.</ref>\n\nOn 22 September fighting broke out between Republican Guard troops commanded by Saleh's son Ahmed, and dissidents loyal to General [[Ali Mohsen al-Ahmar]]. Fighting which had been concentrated since 18 September in the city centre and at Change Square spread on to Sanaa's Al-Hasaba district, where gunmen loyal to powerful dissident tribal chief Sheikh Sadiq al-Ahmar traded fire with followers of [[Saghir bin Aziz]], a tribesman loyal to Saleh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/20119227516362990.html |title=Deadly fighting rages through Yemeni capital |access-date=26 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928113253/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/20119227516362990.html |archive-date=28 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Return of Ali Abdullah Saleh===\nOn 23 September, Yemeni state-television announced that Saleh had returned to the country after three months amid increasing turmoil in a week that saw increased gun battles on the streets of Sana\u02bda and more than 100 deaths.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/201192344820432439.html Yemen's Saleh calls for ceasefire on return] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923172319/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/09/201192344820432439.html |date=23 September 2011 }}. Al Jazeera.net.</ref>\n\nAs of 1 October 2011, [[Human Rights Watch]] was able to confirm 225 deaths and over 1000 wounded, many from firearms, since the Arab Spring protests began in Yemen.<ref>Human Rights Watch. \"UN Human Rights Council: Yemen Resolution Falls Far Short.\" 1 October 2011. Retrieved 8 October 2011 [https://www.hrw.org/news/2011/10/01/un-human-rights-council-yemen-resolution-falls-far-short Human Rights Watch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317101435/https://www.hrw.org/news/2011/10/01/un-human-rights-council-yemen-resolution-falls-far-short |date=17 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>Human Rights Watch. \"Yemen: Protester Killings Show Perils of Immunity Deal.\" 20 September 2011. Retrieved 8 October 2011 [https://www.hrw.org/news/2011/09/20/yemen-protester-killings-show-perils-immunity-deal Human Rights Watch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226191649/https://www.hrw.org/news/2011/09/20/yemen-protester-killings-show-perils-immunity-deal |date=26 February 2017 }}</ref> According to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], photojournalist [[Jamal al-Sharaabi]] from [[Al-Masdar]] was the first press fatality of the Yemeni uprising and killed while covering a nonviolent demonstration at the [[Sana'a University|Sana\u02bda University]] 18 March 2011, but [[Reporters Without Borders]] reported that [[Mohamed Yahia Al-Malayia]], a reporter from Al-Salam, was shot at Change Square on the same day but died later.<ref>Reporters Without Borders. \"Journalists targeted by governments desperate to control news.\" 24 March 2011. Retrieved 9 October 2011. [http://en.rsf.org/middle-east-north-africa-journalists-targeted-by-23-03-2011,39852.html RSF] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111021010145/http://en.rsf.org/middle-east-north-africa-journalists-targeted-by-23-03-2011,39852.html |date=21 October 2011 }}</ref> Camera operator [[Hassan al-Wadhaf]] captured his own death on camera while assigned a protest in Sana\u02bda on 24 September 2011.<ref>Committee to Protect Journalists. \"Jamal al-Sharaabi\" 18 March 2011. Retrieved 9 October 2011 [http://cpj.org/killed/2011/jamal-al-sharaabi.php CPJ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303231656/https://cpj.org/killed/2011/jamal-al-sharaabi.php |date=3 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>Committee to Protect Journalists. \"Hassan al-Wadhaf\" 24 September 2011. Retrieved 9 October 2011 [http://www.cpj.org/killed/2011/hassan-al-wadhaf.php CPJ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004174829/https://www.cpj.org/killed/2011/hassan-al-wadhaf.php |date=4 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October, the [[Nobel Committee]] announced that protest leader [[Tawakel Karman]] would share the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] with Liberian President [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] and Liberian activist [[Leymah Gbowee]]. Karman was the first Yemeni citizen and first Arab woman to win a [[Nobel Prize]].\n\nOn December 4, 2017, Ali Abdullah Saleh was killed by Houthi militia in Yemen following days of conflict. His nephew, Tarek Saleh, was thought to have been killed the following day as the fighting between Saleh soldiers and Houthis continued.   A few weeks later Tarek Saleh appeared in Aden with various stories about his escape including using women's clothing<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/12/houthi-media-ali-abdullah-saleh-killed-sanaa-171204123328290.html|title=Yemen: Ex-President Ali Abdullah Saleh killed|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211091948/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/12/houthi-media-ali-abdullah-saleh-killed-sanaa-171204123328290.html|archive-date=11 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Power-transfer deal===\nOn 23 November 2011, Saleh flew to [[Riyadh]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] to sign the [[Gulf Co-operation Council]] plan for political transition, which he had previously spurned. Upon signing the document, he agreed to legally transfer the powers of the presidency to his deputy, Vice President [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]] within 30 days and formally step down by the [[2012 Yemeni presidential election|presidential elections on 21 February 2012]], in exchange of immunity from prosecution for him and his family.<ref name=\"survivor\">{{cite news|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle09.asp?xfile=data/middleeast/2011/November/middleeast_November598.xml|work=Khaleej Times|title=Saleh, Yemen's great survivor, finally quits power|date=23 November 2011|accessdate=23 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126135222/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle09.asp?xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2011%2FNovember%2Fmiddleeast_November598.xml|archive-date=26 November 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 January 2012, the [[Assembly of Representatives of Yemen]] approved the immunity law. It also nominated Vice President Hadi as its candidate for the upcoming presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/22/world/middleeast/yemens-parliament-approves-immunity-for-president-saleh.html|title=Yemen Legislators Approve Immunity for the President|last=Kasinof|first=Laura|date=21 January 2012|accessdate=22 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122004822/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/22/world/middleeast/yemens-parliament-approves-immunity-for-president-saleh.html|archive-date=22 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Saleh left Yemen on the next day to seek medical treatment in the [[United States]], and is reportedly seeking exile in [[Oman]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/23/world/middleeast/yemeni-president-leaves-heading-for-us.html |title=Yemen Leader Leaves for Medical Care in New York |access-date=26 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113142726/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/23/world/middleeast/yemeni-president-leaves-heading-for-us.html |archive-date=13 January 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA [[2012 Yemeni presidential election|presidential election]] was held in Yemen on 21 February 2012. With a report claims that it has 65 percent of its turnout, Hadi won 99.8% of the vote. [[Abd Rabbuh Mansur al-Hadi]] was taken the oath of office in Yemen's parliament on 25 February 2012. Saleh returned home at the same day to attend Hadi's presidency inauguration.<ref name=nytnewpres/> After months of protests, Saleh had resigned from the presidency and formally transfer power to his successor, marking the end of his 33-year rule.<ref name=\"google.com\"/> As part of the agreement, al-Hadi will oversee the drafting of a new constitution and serve only two years, until new parliamentary and presidential elections are held in 2014.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-17177720 | work=BBC News | title=Yemen's president Ali Abdullah Saleh cedes power | date=27 February 2012 | access-date=21 June 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429043931/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-17177720 | archive-date=29 April 2018 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Domestic responses==\nOn 27 January, Yemeni Interior Minister [[Mutaher al-Masri]] said that \"Yemen is not like Tunisia.\"<ref name=\"Yemen isnt Tunisia\">\n{{cite news\n| url = http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2011/01/27/Yemen-isnt-Tunisia-government-says/UPI-42591296153057/\n| title = Yemen Isn't Tunisia, Government Says\n| agency = United Press International\n| date = 27 January 2011\n| access-date = 27 January 2011\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110130050814/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2011/01/27/Yemen-isnt-Tunisia-government-says/UPI-42591296153057/\n| archive-date = 30 January 2011\n| url-status = live\n| df = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn 2 February, President Ali Abdullah Saleh said that he would freeze the constitutional amendment process under way. He also vowed not to pass on the reins of power to his son: \"No extension, no inheritance, no resetting the clock;\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n| url= http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/02/2011228541277951.html\n| title= Yemen president not to extend term\n| publisher= Al Jazeera\n| date= 2 February 2011\n| accessdate= 2 February 2011\n| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110202134046/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/africa/2011/02/2011228541277951.html\n| archive-date= 2 February 2011\n| url-status= live\n| df= dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> and that he would quit in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | author = Sinjab, Lina | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12343166 | title = Yemen President Ali Abdullah Saleh to quit in 2013 | work = BBC News | date = 30 October 2010 | accessdate = 4 February 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110204120022/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12343166 | archive-date = 4 February 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He also called for [[national unity government]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mazen |first=Maram |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-02/mubarak-step-down-pledge-fails-to-calm-protests-as-unrest-spreads-to-yemen.html |title=Gunfire in Cairo as Mubarak Allies Battle Protesters |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=4 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204193923/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-02/mubarak-step-down-pledge-fails-to-calm-protests-as-unrest-spreads-to-yemen.html |archive-date=4 February 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He further promised direct elections of provincial governors and to re-open voter registration for the April election after complaints that about 1.5 million Yemenis could not sign on to the voter rolls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/201121210345525985.html |title=Middle East rulers make concessions |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=12 February 2011 |accessdate=13 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213085609/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/02/201121210345525985.html |archive-date=13 February 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 1 March, Saleh blamed the United States and Israel over the conflict.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nOn 10 March, he announced a referendum on moving to a parliamentary system of government would be held later in the year. A spokesperson for the anti-government protesters said this was \"too little, too late.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12697077 | title = Yemen: President Saleh Announces 'Parliamentary System' | work = BBC News | date = 1 March 2011 | accessdate = 11 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110311052321/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12697077 | archive-date = 11 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He said a new constitution would guarantee the separation of legislative and executive powers and prepare for a new election.<ref>{{cite news |title=New constitution promised for Yemen |publisher=Al Jazeera |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201131073622898186.html |date=10 March 2011 |accessdate=10 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310092928/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201131073622898186.html |archive-date=10 March 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 20 March, Saleh fired the cabinet, Saleh fired all members of his [[Cabinet of Yemen]] on the same day including Prime Minister [[Ali Muhammad Mujawar]] and vice-Prime Ministers [[Al-Rashad Mouhmmed Ala\u00efmy]], [[Abdul-Karim Al-Ar'haby]] and [[Sadiq Amin Abu-Rass]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Yemeni President Fires Government | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12800887 | date = 20 March 2011 | accessdate = 21 March 2011 | work = BBC News | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110321005423/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12800887 | archive-date = 21 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> but asked them to remain in a caretaker role until he forms a new one.<ref name=\"AJYemen20Mar\">{{cite news | title = Yemen President Fires Cabinet | publisher = Al Jazeera | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320180579476.html | date = 20 March 2011 | accessdate = 20 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110321111228/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320180579476.html | archive-date = 21 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe leader of the [[Yemeni Congregation for Reform|Yemeni Congregation for Reform (Islah)]], the largest opposition party in Yemen, Mohammed al-Sabry, stated, \"We want constitutional amendments but we want amendments that don't lead to the continuance of the ruler and the inheritance of power to his children.\"<ref name=\"afreuters\" /> He also doubted Saleh's pledge not to seek re-election. Al-Sabry said Saleh made a promise in 2006 not to run, but then failed to fulfill his pledge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apnews.myway.com//article/20110202/D9L4JL1O0.html |title=Yemeni president says he won't seek another term |publisher=Apnews.myway.com |date=2 February 2011 |accessdate=4 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325165529/http://apnews.myway.com//article/20110202/D9L4JL1O0.html |archive-date=25 March 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Saleh, in a letter passed to opposition groups, offered to hold a referendum on a new constitution, then a parliamentary election, followed by a presidential poll before the end of 2011. The opposition groups said they were studying the offer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yemeni president offers early elections |publisher=Al Jazeera |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201132323226372234.html |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=24 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325114146/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201132323226372234.html |archive-date=25 March 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Saleh issued a statement that he \"has accepted the five points submitted by the JMP, including formation of a government of national unity and a national committee to draft a new constitution, drafting a new electoral law, and holding a constitutional referendum, parliamentary elections and a presidential vote by the end of the year<ref>Jamjoom, Mohammed (24 March 2011).  [http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/03/23/yemen.protests/index.html \"Yemen's Leader Says He Will Accept Transition Plan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324152616/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/meast/03/23/yemen.protests/index.html |date=24 March 2011 }}. [[CNN]].</ref> although it was later reported that negotiations between Saleh and the opposition had stalled.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yemen transition talks stalled|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011327205340499890.html|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=27 March 2011|accessdate=31 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190526/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011327205340499890.html|archive-date=5 April 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, at a meeting with Mohammed al-Yadoumi, head of the Islah party, Yemen's president made a new offer, proposing he stays in office until elections are held at the end of the year but transferring his powers to a caretaker government, with a prime-minister appointed by the opposition. The opposition promptly rejected the offer, with a spokesman calling it \"an attempt to prolong the survival of regime\".<ref name=\"AJYem30Mar\">{{cite news|title=Yemen's Saleh 'makes new offer to protesters'|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201133014584368624.html|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=30 March 2011|accessdate=31 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110331103920/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/201133014584368624.html|archive-date=31 March 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Resignations from the ruling party and government===\n{{See also|Cabinet of Yemen}}\n* Head of the ruling party's foreign affairs committee and the Advisor to the Prime Minister, [[H.E Dr. Mohammed Abdul Majeed Qubaty]]<ref name=\"guardianlivemarch18\"/><ref name=\"yahooAUmarch20-quit\"/>\n* Head of the finance committee of parliament [[Fathi Tawfiq Abdulrahim]]<ref name=\"jazeerampsmarch5\">[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/20113514455840795.html \"Yemen MPs Quit Ruling Party\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190400/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/20113514455840795.html |date=5 April 2011 }}. [[Al Jazeera]]. 5 March 2011.</ref>\n* Deputy Ministry of Culture (Yemen) [[Sam Yahya Al-Ahmar]]<ref name=\"jazeerampsmarch5\"/>\n* Deputy Ministry of Youth and Sports (Yemen) [[Hashid Abdullah al-Ahmar]]<ref name=\"jazeerampsmarch5\"/>\n* MP [[Ali Al-Imrani]], from [[Al Bayda' Governorate]]<ref name=\"jazeerampsmarch5\"/>\n* Businessman Nabil Al-Khameri<ref name=\"jazeerampsmarch5\"/>\n* Ministry of Tourism (Yemen)] [[Nabil Hasan al-Faqih]], from his post and the ruling party<ref name=\"guardianlivemarch18\">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/mar/18/libya-military-action-live-updates#block-55 \"Libya Military Action: Live Updates\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510174332/https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/mar/18/libya-military-action-live-updates#block-55 |date=10 May 2017 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 18 March 2011.</ref><ref name=\"yahooAUmarch20-quit\"/>\n* Minister of Culture and Yemeni Shura Council member [[Abdulwahab al-Rawhani]], from the ministry and council<ref name=\"guardianlivemarch18\"/><ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-03/19/c_13786741.htm \"Death Toll Rises to 45 as Emergency Declared in Yemen Amid Mounting Protests\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320080303/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-03/19/c_13786741.htm |date=20 March 2011 }}. [[Xinhua News Agency]].  19 March 2011.</ref>\n* Ambassador to Russia Dr. [[Mohammed Saleh Ahmed Al-Helali]]<ref name=\"guardianlivemarch18\"/>\n* Party's central committee member [[Jalal Faqira]] who also heads the political science department at Sana\u02bda University<ref name=\"guardianlivemarch18\"/>\n* Assistant Secretary General of the Cabinet [[Mohammad Sewar]]<ref name=\"yahooAUmarch20-quit\">[http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/-/world/9041205/yemeni-troops-on-streets-as-two-party-members-quit/ \"Yemeni Troops on Streets as Two Party Members Quit\"]. [[Yahoo! News]]. 20 March 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119084100/http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/-/world/9041205/yemeni-troops-on-streets-as-two-party-members-quit/ |date=19 November 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"newsYemenMar19-quit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsyemen.net/en/view_news.asp?sub_no=3_2011_03_19_40330Yemen: |title=Officials Resign from Ruling Party Following Violence Against Protesters |publisher=News Yemen |accessdate=19 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207024311/http://www.newsyemen.net/en/view_news.asp?sub_no=3_2011_03_19_40330Yemen%3A |archivedate=7 February 2012 }}</ref>\n* Head of the state news agency and a ruling party member [[Nasr Taha Mustafa]]<ref name=\"guardian1\">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/19/yemen-sanaa-state-emergency-troops \"Security Forces Blanket Yemen Capital To Enforce State of Emergency\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203082047/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/19/yemen-sanaa-state-emergency-troops |date=3 February 2017 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''.  19 March 2011.</ref>\n* Ambassador to Lebanon [[Fay\u00e7al Amine Abourrass]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5igr1rxe02d-TWWIdydUaSR8yi4nA?docId=CNG.0571c1ac6567bdad38af266d2e0abe05.531 |title=AFP: Yemen Rights Minister Resigns To Protest Crackdown |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |publisher=Google News |accessdate=23 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224105314/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5igr1rxe02d-TWWIdydUaSR8yi4nA?docId=CNG.0571c1ac6567bdad38af266d2e0abe05.531 |archivedate=24 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lorientlejour.com/category/Liban/article/695234/Demission_de_lambassadeur_du_Yemen_au_Liban_suite_au_massacre_de_Sanaa.html |title=L'Orient-Le Jour |work=[[L'Orient Le Jour]] |accessdate=21 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002074429/http://www.lorientlejour.com/category/Liban/article/695234/Demission_de_lambassadeur_du_Yemen_au_Liban_suite_au_massacre_de_Sanaa.html |archive-date=2 October 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Mohamed Saleh Qara'a]], a prominent member of the ruling party<ref name=\"guardian1\"/>\n* Human Rights Ministry (Yemen) [[Huda al-Baan]], from her post and the ruling party<ref name=\"inquirer1\">[http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/world/view/20110320-326612/Yemen-rights-minister-resigns-to-protest-crackdown \"Yemen Rights Minister Resigns To Protest Crackdown\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325200412/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/world/view/20110320-326612/Yemen-rights-minister-resigns-to-protest-crackdown |date=25 March 2011 }}.  ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''.  19 March 2011.</ref>\n* Undersecretary at the Human Rights Ministry [[Ali Taysir]]<ref name=\"inquirer1\"/>\n* Representative to the [[Arab League]] [[Abdel-Malik Mansour]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Algeria]] [[Jamal Awadh Nasser]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/> (denied by the government<ref name=\"yobserver23march\">al-Kibsi, Mohammed (23 March 2011).  [https://archive.today/20130209225129/http://www.yobserver.com/front-page/10021001.html \"Yemen Officials Blame Aljazeera for False Reports\"]. ''[[Yemen Observer]]''.</ref>)\n* Ambassador to [[Belgium]] [[Abdul-Wali al-Shameri]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Canada]] [[Khalid Bahah]]{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n* Ambassador to [[China]] [[Marwan Abdullah Abdulwahab Noman]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/> (denied by the government<ref name=\"yobserver23march\"/>)\n* Ambassador to [[Czech Republic]] [[Salem Yahya Alkharejah]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Egypt]] [[Abdul-Wali al-Shameri]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Indonesia]] [[Abdulwahed Mohamed Fara]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Iraq]] [[Abdul-Wali al-Shameri]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Jordan]] [[Shaea Muhssin]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Kuwait]] [[Khaled Sheikh|Dr.Khaled Sheikh]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Oman]] [[Ahmad Daifallah Al-Azeib]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Pakistan]] [[Abdu Ali Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to [[Saudi Arabia]] [[Mohammed Ali al-Ahwal]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110322183038/http://blogs.aljazeera.net/live/middle-east/yemen-live-blog-march-21 \"Yemen Live Blog&nbsp;\u2013 March 21\"], [[Al Jazeera]].  21 March 2011.</ref><ref name=\"guardianlivemarch21\">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/mar/21/yemen-army-commanders-defect \"Yemen Unrest&nbsp;\u2013 Live Coverage\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304233732/http://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/mar/21/yemen-army-commanders-defect |date=4 March 2016 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 21 March 2011.</ref>\n* Ambassador to [[Spain]] [[Salim Yahya al-Kharega]];<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/> (denied by the government<ref name=\"yobserver23march\"/>)\n* Ambassador to [[Syria]] [[Abdel-Wahhab Tawaf]]<ref>{{cite news | title = Yemen Ambassador to Syria Resigns from Post, Party | work = [[The Jerusalem Post]] | url = http://www.jpost.com/Headlines/Article.aspx?id=213120 | date = 21 March 2011 | accessdate = 21 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110321105423/http://www.jpost.com/Headlines/Article.aspx?id=213120 | archive-date = 21 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Ambassador to [[Qatar]] [[Yahya Hussain Al-Aarashi]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* Ambassador to the [[United Nations]] [[Abdullah al-Saidi]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/><ref>[http://www.ipacademy.org/events/podcasts/225-ambassador-abdullah-m-alsaidi-joins-ipi.html \"Ambassador Abdullah M. Alsaidi Joins IPI\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110922110849/http://www.ipacademy.org/events/podcasts/225-ambassador-abdullah-m-alsaidi-joins-ipi.html |date=22 September 2011 }} [[International Peace Institute]]. 30 March 2011.</ref>\n* [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires]] to [[Tunisia]]<ref name=\"jazeeralivemarch21\"/>\n* [[Major General]] [[Ali Mohsen al-Ahmar]] (Ali Mohsen Saleh), head of the North Western Military Zone, and three of his brigadiers:<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/21/yemen-regime-army-chiefs-defect \"Yemen Showdown Looms as Army Loyalties Divide\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224230957/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/21/yemen-regime-army-chiefs-defect |date=24 February 2017 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. 21 March 2011.</ref><ref name=\"jazeeraarmymarch21\">[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320180579476.html \"Top Army Commanders Defect in Yemen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321111228/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320180579476.html |date=21 March 2011 }}. [[Al Jazeera]]. 21 March 2011.</ref>\n** [[Brigadier]] [[Mohammed Ali Mohsen]], head of the Eastern Division<ref name=\"jazeeraarmymarch21\"/>\n** [[Brigadier]] [[Hameed Al-Qushaibi]], head of brigade 310 in Omran area<ref name=\"jazeeraarmymarch21\"/>\n** [[Brigadier]] [[Nasser Eljahori]], head of brigade 121<ref name=\"jazeeraarmymarch21\"/>\n* Sixty officers of the province of Hadramout and fifty officers from the Ministry of Interior{{citation needed|date=March 2011}}\n* [[Abdallah al-Qahdi]], a senior military general from Aden<ref>Finn, Tom (21 March 2011).  [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/21/yemen-military-commanders-opposition-tanks \"Yemen Military Commanders Join Opposition as Tanks Take to the Streets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712052337/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/mar/21/yemen-military-commanders-opposition-tanks |date=12 July 2017 }}.  ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref>\n\n===Arrests and repression===\n[[File:Yemeni soldiers from the 1st Armoured Division.JPG|thumb|Yemeni soldiers from the 1st Armoured Division on 60th Street in Sana\u02bda, 22 May 2011]]\n[[File:Yemen protest3.jpg|thumb|A television reporter in the middle of protesters in [[Sana'a|Sana\u02bda]]]]\nOn 23 January, Tawakel Karman was detained and charged with \"'inciting disorder and chaos' and organising unauthorised demonstrations and marches\".<ref name=\"ifex_karman_freed\">{{cite web| title = Authorities Release Journalists for Fear of Tunisia-Style Unrest | publisher =[[International Freedom of Expression Exchange]] | date = 26 January 2011 | url =http://www.ifex.org/yemen/2011/01/26/karman_released/ | accessdate = 1 February 2011 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110131182831/http://ifex.org/yemen/2011/01/26/karman_released/ | archivedate = 31 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Karman was a leader of two student rallies in Sana\u02bda and called for the overthrow of Saleh's regime.<ref name=\"aljaz_karman_detained\"/> Her husband said her whereabouts were not known.<ref name=\"aljaz_karman_detained\" /> Several hundred students protested outside Sana\u02bda University demanding her release.<ref name=\"aljaz_karman_detained\" /> Thousands of people protested against the arrest of Karman and other protestors by a sit-in outside of the prosecutor's office. She was freed 30 hours after her arrest on parole, with the condition not to violate \"public order and the law\".<ref name=\"ifex_karman_freed\" /> Karman returned to participating in demonstrations hours after her release.<ref name=\"ifex_karman_freed\" />\n\nOn 14 March, security forces raided an apartment shared by four Western journalists and deported them. [[Reporters Without Borders]] condemned the action and noted that two other foreign journalists were also deported two days earlier. The [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] also condemned the expulsions. They also said that two Yemeni journalists informed them that a group of twenty people, believed to be government supporters, went to the Yemeni Journalists' Syndicate in Sana\u02bda day earlier{{When|date=March 2011}} and threatened to burn it down.<ref name=\"AJYemen15Mar\">{{cite news | title = Yemen Deports Foreign Journalists | publisher = Al Jazeera | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011314212132903514.html | date = 15 March 2011 | accessdate = 15 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110315003511/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011314212132903514.html | archive-date = 15 March 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> They further said that Yemeni journalists are facing increasing harassment.<ref>{{cite web| title = Attacks on Journalists in Yemen, Sudan Amid Street Protests| url = http://cpj.org/2011/01/attacks-on-journalists-in-yemen-sudan-amid-street.php| publisher = [[Committee to Protect Journalists]]| accessdate = 1 February 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110201000655/http://cpj.org/2011/01/attacks-on-journalists-in-yemen-sudan-amid-street.php| archive-date = 1 February 2011| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==International reactions==\n{{main|International reactions to the Yemeni revolution}}\nThe Yemeni government's response to protests prompted a backlash even from traditional allies like the [[United States]]<ref name=\"Sudarsan Raghavan\">{{cite news| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/18/AR2011021804066.html| title = In Yemen, Government Loyalists Harden Their Attacks on Protesters| author = Raghavan, Sudarsan| work = [[The Washington Post]]| date = 18 February 2011| accessdate = 17 May 2011| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110430154822/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/18/AR2011021804066.html| archive-date = 30 April 2011| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/67892/bernard-haykel/saudi-arabias-yemen-dilemma|work=Foreign Affairs|first=Bernard|last=Haykel|authorlink=Bernard Haykel|title=Saudi Arabia's Yemen dilemma|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728020636/http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/67892/bernard-haykel/saudi-arabias-yemen-dilemma|archive-date=28 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A number of national governments have called on President Saleh to resign, and the [[Gulf Co-operation Council]] introduced an initiative calling upon Saleh to relinquish power in favor of a new, democratically elected government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13190305|work=BBC News|date=25 April 2011|accessdate=7 August 2011|title=Yemen: Opposition backs GCC plan for Saleh resignation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429044313/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13190305|archive-date=29 April 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Obama administration, however, supported \"a transitional framework that preserved privileges for established political and military elements of the old regime, rather than respond to the groundswell of genuine support\u2014no, demand\u2014for political pluralism and a civil state.\"<ref>Jillian Schwedler and   Stacey Philbrick Yadav. 6 May 2015. \"The Moral Economy of Distance\". [https://merip.org/2015/05/the-moral-economy-of-distance-in-the-yemeni-crisis Middle East Research and Information Project website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306234959/https://merip.org/2015/05/the-moral-economy-of-distance-in-the-yemeni-crisis/ |date=6 March 2019 }}.</ref>\n\nOn 7 October 2011, [[Tawakul Karman]] was awarded the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] for her visible role as a woman in the Arab Spring movement and as a human right activist in Yemen. She shared the Prize with Liberian President [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] and Liberian peace activist [[Leymah Gbowee]]. Before their prizes were awarded, only 12 other women had ever been granted the award.<ref>BBC News. \"Three women share Nobel Peace Prize\" 7 October 2011. Retrieved 8 October 2011. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15211104 BBC News] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201124939/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15211104 |date=1 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n===Use of pink===\n[[File:Yemen protest1.jpg|Protesters with pink signs and headwear|thumb]]\n{{main|Colour revolution}}\nYemeni protesters wore [[pink]] ribbons to symbolise the \"[[Tunisian revolution|Jasmine Revolution]]\" and indicate their non-violent intent.<ref name=\"tom finn\" /> Shawki al-Qadi, a lawmaker and opposition figure, said pink was chosen to represent [[love]] and to signal that the protests would be peaceful.<ref name=\"Code Pink\">\n{{cite news\n| last= Bakri\n| first= Nada\n| url= http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/27/yemens-opposition-goes-to-code-pink/\n| title= Yemen's Opposition Goes to Code Pink\n| work= [[The New York Times]]\n| date= 27 January 2011\n| access-date= 27 January 2011\n| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110128213504/http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/27/yemens-opposition-goes-to-code-pink/\n| archive-date= 28 January 2011\n| url-status= live\n| df= dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> The preponderance of pink ribbons in the demonstrations showed the level of planning that went into the protests.<ref name=\"Code Pink\" />\n\n===Opposition factions===\n{{See also|Political parties in Yemen}}\n[[File:2011\u20132012 Yemeni revolution (from Al Jazeera) - 20110301-05.jpg|thumb|Tens of thousands of protesters marching to [[Sana'a University|Sana\u02bda University]], joined for the first time by opposition parties]]\nAccording to [[Al Jazeera]] in late February, the deeply fractured opposition includes the [[Joint Meeting Parties]] (JMP; formed in 2002), [[Al-Islah (Yemen)|Islah]] (also known as Yemeni Congregation for Reform and the major member of JMP), the al-Ahmar family, and various insurrection groups including the [[Houthis]] in the north and the [[South Yemen Movement]] in the south. These groups include socialist, Islamist and tribal elements with differing goals. Islah, which [[2003 Yemeni parliamentary election|currently holds about twenty per cent]] of the seats in the legislature, includes some members of the Ahmar family, Yemen's [[Muslim Brotherhood#Yemen|Muslim Brotherhood]], and [[Salafi]] preacher [[Abdul Majid al-Zindani]], labeled a \"specially designated global terrorist\" by the US. The JMP also includes the Yemeni Socialist Party (YSP), Al-Haq, the Unionist party, and the Popular Forces Union party. The al-Ahmar sons&nbsp;\u2013 [[Sadek al-Ahmar]] and [[Hamid al-Ahmar]]&nbsp;\u2013 whose late father was a former leader of the Hashid tribal confederation, want power. The Southern Movement has temporarily dropped its calls for secession with calls for Saleh's ouster.<ref>Staff (28 February 2011). [https://web.archive.org/web/20110306030326/http://english.aljazeera.net/indepth/spotlight/yemen/2011/02/2011228141453986337.html \"Who's Who in Yemen's Opposition\"]. [[Al Jazeera]]. Retrieved 16 May 2011.</ref>\n\n[[human rights in Yemen|Yemeni human-rights activists]] and students disagree with [[Political parties in Yemen|political parties]] regarding tactics for political change in Yemen. Some political parties have called for reform to take place under President Saleh, while students and human rights activists have wished to \"channel the momentum of the [[Arab Spring|2010\u20132011 uprisings in the region]].\"<ref name=\"WP_Yemeni_tactics\" /> In late January, a lawyer and human-rights activist involved in organising protests, Khaled al-Anesi, stated \"There is a popular movement and a political movement in Yemen. But there is no support from the political parties for the popular movement, which is not organised. It is still weak and in the beginning stages.\"<ref name=\"WP_Yemeni_tactics\">{{cite news | author = Raghavan, Sudarsan | title = In Yemen, Calls for Revolution But Many Hurdles | date = 31 January 2011 | work = [[The Washington Post]] | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/30/AR2011013003175.html | accessdate = 16 May 2011 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110430150939/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/30/AR2011013003175.html | archivedate = 30 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that in the absence of obvious candidates for the presidency, the transition of power is likely to be controlled by those who made the pre-emptive strike against him: [[Hamid al-Ahmar]] of Islah and the JMP, radical cleric [[Abdul Majid al-Zindani]], and Islamist-allied General [[Ali Mohsen al-Ahmar]] (also called [[Ali Mohsen Saleh]]).<ref>{{registration required|date=May 2011}} Fielding-Smith, Abigail; Khalaf, Roula (21 March 2011).  [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f4a1f49e-53f0-11e0-8bd7-00144feab49a.html#axzz1HO6jZuzd \"Feared General Regarded as Kingmaker\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325071908/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f4a1f49e-53f0-11e0-8bd7-00144feab49a.html#axzz1HO6jZuzd |date=25 March 2011 }}. ''[[Financial Times]]''. Retrieved 21 March 2011.</ref>\n\n====Southern groups====\nSouthern secessionist groups said they were holding three Yemeni soldiers kidnapped towards the end of January. On 2 February, clashes in the south also resulted in three injuries.<ref>{{cite news|date=2 February 2011 |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iny54OZvAJq5sX9zhloNLQxiGxvA?docId=CNG.4aae4371b956b57599c1a3203f206025.3f1 |title=Three Wounded in South Yemen Clashes |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |publisher=Google News |accessdate=16 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316051124/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iny54OZvAJq5sX9zhloNLQxiGxvA?docId=CNG.4aae4371b956b57599c1a3203f206025.3f1 |archivedate=16 March 2011 }}</ref> A growing number of protesters in the north sees with interest the rise of the [[South Yemen Movement]], maybe hoping that the southern secessionists may overthrow the government.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\n====Al Qaeda====\nOn 6 March, [[Al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]] (AQAP) claimed responsibility for the shooting of five soldiers two separate attacks during the ongoing protests. Four of the soldiers were killed in [[Ma'rib Governorate]] when the perpetrators opened fire on a passing military vehicle. Two of the soldiers were part of the [[Yemeni Republican Guard|Republican Guard]]. The other death was that of an army colonel who was shot as he went shopping in [[Zinjibar]], [[Abyan Governorate]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/20113685346945172.html | title = Yemeni Soldiers Killed in Attacks | publisher = Al Jazeera | date = 6 March 2011 | accessdate = 16 May 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190533/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/20113685346945172.html | archive-date = 5 April 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2011, AQAP declared an \"Islamic [[Emirate]]\" in the southern [[Abyan Governorate]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Craig, Iona | url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-04-01-yemen01_ST_N.htm | title = Amid Region's Unrest, al-Qaeda Makes Inroads in Yemen | work = [[USA Today]] | date = 1 April 2011 | accessdate = 16 May 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110515221352/http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-04-01-yemen01_ST_N.htm | archive-date = 15 May 2011 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Joint Meeting Parties====\nOn 2 March, six members of the JMP issued a five-point list of demands: right to demonstrate, investigations into violence, peaceful transition of government, time schedule within current year, and dialogue with those both inside and outside of Yemen.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.yemenpeaceproject.org/wordpress/?p=263 \"San'a Bulletin #4\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322021720/http://www.yemenpeaceproject.org/wordpress/?p=263 |date=22 March 2011 }}. The Yemen Peace Project. 3 March 2011.</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the JMP issued a statement that any new regime, after Saleh's fall, would be a strong ally in the \"War on Terror\".<ref>[http://www.yemenpost.net/Detail123456789.aspx?ID=3&SubID=3383&MainCat=3 \" Opposition Assures Any 'New Regime Will Be Strong Ally in War on Terror'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813140457/http://www.yemenpost.net/Detail123456789.aspx?ID=3&SubID=3383&MainCat=3 |date=13 August 2011 }}. ''[[Yemen Post]]''. 4 April 2011.</ref>\n\n====Alliance of Yemeni Tribes====\n{{main|Alliance of Yemeni Tribes}}\nA group of anti-government tribes, most prominently the [[Hashid]] tribal federation, declared the formation of the Alliance of Yemeni Tribes on 30 July. The Alliance is headed by Sheikh [[Sadiq al-Ahmar]], the leader of the Hashid and a former ally of President Saleh, and is aligned with [[Yemen Army]] defectors under the leadership of General [[Ali Mohsen al-Ahmar]]. In its first declaration, it vowed solidarity with the protest movement and warned the government that any attack on protesters or areas under the control of the Yemeni opposition would be seen as attacks on the tribes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/World/Story/STIStory_696854.html |work=Straits Times |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=7 August 2011 |title=Yemeni tribes form coalition against Saleh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807065811/http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/World/Story/STIStory_696854.html |archivedate=7 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.yemenpeaceproject.org/wordpress/?p=269 San\u2018a Bulletin #5] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190810/http://www.yemenpeaceproject.org/wordpress/?p=269 |date=5 April 2011 }}, The Yemen Peace Project, 8 March 2011.</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2011, a coordination council of the Sana\u02bda University protestors presented a list of seven demands, starting with the removal of Saleh and the creation of a temporary presidential council made up of representatives drawn from Yemen's four main political powers along with one appointed by the national security and military establishment. Many members of the Revolutionary Coalition of Youth for Peaceful Change (12 organizations) and the Organization of Liberal Yemeni Youth appear to be represented by this coordination council.<ref>{{last=Al-Sakkaf|first=Nadia|authorlink=Nadia Al-Sakkaf|date=14 March 2011|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315021057/http://www.yementimes.com/defaultdet.aspx?SUB_ID=35747 |title=Yemeni Youth Movements Consolidate|work=[[Yemen Times]]}}</ref> On 17 March they sent a letter to US President Barack Obama, copying British PM David Cameron and EU President John Bruton, explaining their group, positions and proposals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Novak, Jane|date=22 March 2011|url=http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2011/03/22/yemens-youth-coordinating-council-writes-president-obama/|title=Yemen's Youth Coordinating Council Writes President Obama|publisher=Armies of Liberation|accessdate=22 March 2011|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120701151448/http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2011/03/22/yemens-youth-coordinating-council-writes-president-obama/|archive-date=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2011, the [[Civil Coalition of Youth Revolution]] (CCYR), a Yemen-based civil movement which includes 52 alliances of revolutionary youth activists around Yemen representing more than 10,000 members, released its Statute Draft including its \"vision, revolution objectives, principles, duties, mechanisms and goals of the interim phase\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2011/05/08/yemen-ccyr-declares-continuation-of-uprising-and-releases-statute/|title=Yemen: CCYR declares continuation of uprising and releases statute|publisher=Armies of Liberation|accessdate=8 May 2011|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120707173736/http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2011/05/08/yemen-ccyr-declares-continuation-of-uprising-and-releases-statute/|archive-date=7 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====National Dialogue Conference====\nOn 20 March, the [[National Dialogue Conference]] issued a position paper and list of demands. Their members are the JMP, independents, some [[General People's Congress (Yemen)|General People's Congress]] members, and social figures including political, tribal and businessmen. It is headed by [[Mohammed Basindawa]], an adviser to the president, and Sheik [[Hameed Al-Ahmer]] of Islah is its Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |author=Novak, Jane |date=20 March 2011 |url=http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2010/03/20/the-yemeni-national-dialog-committee-issues-vision-for-national-salvation/ |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110203063005/http://armiesofliberation.com/archives/2010/03/20/the-yemeni-national-dialog-committee-issues-vision-for-national-salvation/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 February 2011 |title=The Yemeni National Dialog Committee Issues Vision for National Salvation |publisher=Armies of Liberation |accessdate=2012-11-07 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Civil Bloc====\nOn 24 March, the Civil Bloc, an umbrella group of civil society organisations, called for a transitional council of nine figures \"not involved with the corruption of the old regime\" to draw up a new constitution over a six-month period ahead of elections.<ref>Johnston, Cynthia; Ghobari, Mohammed 24 March 2011.  [http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/03/24/idINIndia-55848220110324 \"Yemen Forces Clash over Saleh Before Friday Protest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112235428/http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/03/24/idINIndia-55848220110324 |date=12 January 2012 }}. [[Reuters]].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[1962 North Yemen Coup d'\u00e9tat|1962 coup d'\u00e9tat in Yemen]]\n* [[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]]\n* [[2011 Egyptian revolution]]\n* [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula]]\n* [[Democracy in the Middle East]]\n* [[Freedom in the World]]\n* [[Tunisian revolution]]\n* [[1994 civil war in Yemen]]\n* [[List of modern conflicts in the Middle East]]\n* [[Poverty in Yemen]]\n* [[Tawakel Karman]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Alley |first=April Longley |year=2011 |title=Yemen on the Brink: Will Saleh's Resignation Lead to Democratic Reform? |journal=[[Foreign Affairs]] |volume=90 |issue=2|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/67699/april-longley-alley/yemen-on-the-brink }}\n*{{cite book |last=Blum\u0131 |first=Isa |year=2011 |title=Chaos in Yemen: Societal Collapse and the New Authoritarianism |location=London |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9780415780773 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Boucek |editor1-first=Christopher |editor2-last=Ottaway |editor2-first=Marina |year=2010 |title=Yemen on the Brink |location=Washington |publisher=Carnegie Endowment for International Peace |isbn=9780870032530 }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Juneau |first=Thomas |year=2010 |title=Yemen: Prospects for State Failure\u2014Implications and Remedies |journal=[[Middle East Policy]] |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=134\u2013152 |doi=10.1111/j.1475-4967.2010.00456.x }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Thiel |first=Tobias |year=2012 |title=After the Arab Spring: power shift in the Middle East?: Yemen's Arab Spring: from youth revolution to fragile political transition |work=IDEAS reports \u2013 special reports, Kitchen, Nicholas (ed.) SR011. LSE IDEAS, London School of Economics and Political 